<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Manila Stocks Fall Again Due to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Stock Exchange
index today fell by 84.53 points, or 2.9 percent, to close at
2,860.45, the biggest drop in five months.
</P>
<P>
The all shares index also declined 27.48 points, or 2.5
percent, to 948.96 points. It was the biggest percentage decline
since the index was introduced last November, and also the second
time it has closed below 1,000 points since last December.
</P>
<P>
However, turnover rose to 11.38 billion shares worth 3.8
billion pesos (146 million U.S. dollars) compared to 5.9 billion
shares worth 1.62 billion pesos (62.2 million U.S. dollars) posted
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Trading in the exchange was suspended on Monday due to a power
failure in the building where the stock exchange holds its regular
trading. The power failure caused millions of pesos of losses to
the trading floor.
</P>
<P>
In fact, it has been the eighth time that the Stock Exchange
index, a basket of 30 companies, fell in the month. From April
3-9, the index dropped by a total of 200 points in seven
consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the plunge came amid rumors that certain real
estate companies were facing financial problems similar to those
in Thailand, where the financial system has been crippled by loan
defaults to the real estate industry.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Andrew Tan, chairman of Megaworld Properties and
Holdings Inc., attempted to quell speculation that his company
were in financial trouble because of mounting debt.
</P>
<P>
Besides Megaworld, share prices of some other big real estate
developers also suffered heavily with foreign investors adjusting
their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
Banks were also concerned about their loan exposure to the
property industry. In the month, share prices of Metropolitan Bank
and Trust Corporation and Philippine National Bank dropped
sharply.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that there are more than enough similarities
between Manila and Bangkok to spook investors. Both cities have
had a building boom. Like Bangkok, Manila has high interest rates,
some of the worst traffic in Asia and a growing trade deficit that
has hit 14 percent of gross national product.
</P>
<P>
These are all signs that the economy may be overheating, and an
overheated economy often has real estate crashes. However,
analysts said that "there is no cause for such an alarm" in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
They said the Philippine economy is far from being overheated.
It has just been strong enough to create a real estate bubble in
the recent two years, not like Thailand that has enjoyed torrid
economic growth for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
Significantly, real estate in the country still has strength in
places. Although it has a glut and a long pre-sale period to
finance construction, demand still exists in the low and medium
sectors of the residential market, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, banks in the country are also taking measures to
limit their exposure to the property market, analysts said. For
example, the Philippine Commercial International Bank, one of the
largest banks, has lowered its loan ratio to the real estate
industry.
</P>
<P>
After examining commercial banks' real estate loans, the
Central Bank is also looking into the rapid growth of their
foreign currency loans to see if it is posing any danger to the
country's financial system, analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
