<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Santer Accused of Interfering in British Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- European Commission President
Jacques Santer, who attacked British Eurosceptics, has been
accused by Britain's main political party leaders of interfering
in the British general election.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered in Amsterdam Monday, Santer called those
Eurosceptics as "doom merchants" who did not know what they were
taking about.
</P>
<P>
"Do those doom merchants want us to step backwards towards a
Europe only composed of simple trading arrangements?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister John Major, whose Conservative Party is
lagging behind the main opposition Labor Party in the run-up to
the May 1 general election, snatched Santer's controversial speech
as further evidence of the threat of further European integration.
</P>
<P>
"The speech absolutely reinforces the fears I raised a few days
ago. I will keep my feet on the brakes of further European
intergration and he (Labor leader Tony Blair) would put his foot
on the accelerator to a federal Europe," Major told a press
conference today.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party, which is commonly considered as more
pro-European, also distanced itself from Santer by announcing in a
statement that "the British people are perfectly capable of making
up their own minds without intervention from outside."
</P>
<P>
Blair told reporters today, "What Mr Santer says, with all due
respect, is neither here nor there. I disagree with a lot of what
he said."
</P>
<P>
Seeing his speech becoming a hot issue in the British general
election, Santer is quick to make a statement today saying that he
had no intention of interfering in the British election.
</P>
<P>
"We regret that it has become a party political and electoral
issue. It is not our intention to interfere in national elections
or campaigns," Santer's spokesman was quoted by reports from
Brussels as saying today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
