<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's New Policy, Uruguay Accord to Boost World Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- China's new trade policy and the
1993 Uruguay Round accord to lower import tariffs are expected to
boost world trade by 7.8 percent, a research group said here today.
</P>
<P>
The group, of Japan's Economic Planning Agency, said China's
policy of lowering its tariffs from the current 23 percent to 15
percent by the year 2,000 will drive up world trade by 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The policy was pledged by Chinese officials at the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation forum held in Manila last year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the group said, the Uruguay Round accord on
cutting tariffs and lifting import restrictions by participating
countries is likely to expand global trade by 7.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The group said it will call for the Japanese government's
support to China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO)
to help China's implementation of the new trade policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
