<HEADLINE> Key Projects for China's Power Industry in 1996-2000 Period </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The power industry of China will
focus on four key projects in the years through 2010, according to
the World Energy Council Asia-Pacific Forum which opened here
today.
</P>
<P>
As part of the work:
</P>
<P>
-- The country is to build a trans-regional power
interconnection network, which includes the Three Gorges
Transmission Lines Project, centered on the Three Gorges
Hydropower Station and accompanied by the development of large
scale hydropower and thermal power bases. The regional power
network will be interconnected to transmit electricity to the long
distance load center.
</P>
<P>
-- Construction of the rural power network will be
accelerated. By 2000, electricity will extend to all counties,
bringing access to the 70 million people in rural counties who
formerly had no power supply. As a result, 95 percent of the rural
households and 1,000 counties will have electricity.
</P>
<P>
-- Energy conservation will be achieved through technical
innovation. In the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), the
industry will replace eight outdated gw generating units with 12
gw generating units. The retrofits for power grids in urban and
rural areas shall be completed more quickly in order to reduce the
wire loss to 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- More clean coal generation projects will be built. The
industry will actively research and establish the IGCC
demonstration power plants, and the PFBC pilot power plants with
100 mw level and large capacity CFBC boilers. Universal
environmental protection technology such as desulphurization will
be widely applied. The capacity of generating units equipped with
desulphurization facilities will be increased to 10-12 gw, and the
industrial wastewater will not be discharged until it is up to the
standard.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 2000, the total installed generating capacity
will amount to 290 gw. The newly-increased capacity in five years
will reach 80 gw with the average annual growth of 16 gw. The
electricity generation will reach 1,400 twh, with the average
growth at seven percent.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, the thermal power generation will still take the
leading position, covering 70 percent of the total installed
capacity. The hydropower capacity will reach 115 gw, slightly more
than that in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power capacity will reach 20 gw, which will temporarily
alleviate the pressure on coal transportation and environmental
protection in coastal areas. Renewable energy will have a total
capacity of 2.5 gw. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
