<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Jiang's Russia Trip to Greatly Impact World Situation by Xinhua Correspondent Yang Guojun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The four-day state visit to
Russia by Chinese President Jiang Zemin, which started today, will
not only mark a new stage in the Sino-Russian relationship on a
healthy track, but also have a far-reaching impact on the world's
multi-polarization and on the establishment of a new international
political and economic order.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's current visit is the fourth summit between Chinese and
Russian leaders, and each of the previous three meetings since
1992 have pushed the Sino-Russian relationship to new heights.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the bilateral political relationship has
developed soundly and the economic and trade ties have progressed
rapidly. The cooperation between the two neighbors is continuing
to expand while the shared border areas are calm.
</P>
<P>
In December 1992, Russian President Boris Yeltsin visited China
for the first time, and both leaders then signed the "Joint
Communique on the Basis of Sino-Russian Relationship." This
brought the bilateral normal ties to a new level of "mutually
regarding each other as a friendly state."
</P>
<P>
In September 1994, Jiang visited Moscow and both sides once
again signed a joint communique announcing the two states would
establish and promote a "constructive partnership oriented to the
21st century."
</P>
<P>
In April 1996, Yeltsin came to China for the second time, and
both sides signed the third joint communique declaring that the
two countries would develop a strategic partnership of equality
and trust extending beyond the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The current fourth summit is meant to create a new type of
state relationship of "forming into partners, forging a good
neighborhood relationship, equality and mutual trust, mutually
beneficial cooperation and common development."
</P>
<P>
And this new relationship, characterized by "non-alignment,
non-confrontation, targeting at no third parties, mutual equality
and respect, multi-level and multi-faceted cooperation," is
aligned with the trend and requirement of the post-Cold War world
situation. It is also in the fundamental interests of the two
countries and conducive to world peace, stability and development.
</P>
<P>
The new relationship between China and Russia will be a
contribution to the establishment of the world's new political and
economic order. It is also a major practice in this regard, senior
diplomats here have said.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day visit, the two leaders are expected to sign
the fourth joint statement which is believed to focus on world
multi-polarization and on establishment of a new international
order. An agreement on reduction of armed forces on the border
areas between China, Russia, Kazakhstan, Tadzhikistan and
Kirghizstan will also be signed.
</P>
<P>
The fourth statement will explain the shared viewpoints of the
two countries on changes of the post-Cold War world situation and
the international relations.
</P>
<P>
Senior diplomats here claim it is the trend of the times to
establish a new international political and economic order marked
by "peace, stability, fairness and justice" for world peace and
the global development cause.
</P>
<P>
The Five Principles of Peaceful Co-existence and the commonly
acknowledged international laws have become the basis for
establishing a new international order, and differences in social
systems, ideology and values should by no means be used as excuses
for interfering into other countries' internal affairs, or for
power politics or hegemonism.
</P>
<P>
International security is one of the major concerns of the
current international community. In April 1996, China, Russia,
Kazakhstan, Tadzhikistan and Kirghizstan signed in Shanghai an
agreement on strengthening military trust at the border areas.
</P>
<P>
The agreement to be signed in Moscow on the reduction of armed
forces on the border areas will make new room for thought for
developing a new global order, and also help create a new format
for the post-Cold War world security and stability, which is
totally different from the Cold War thinking.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here stress that following the signing of the fourth
joint statement and the military reduction agreements, the
strategic partnership between China and Russia will be further
enriched, and will lead people to re-think the relationship
between big countries in the world multi-polarization
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
