<HEADLINE> Namibian Legal Aid Body Wins UN Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Namibia's Legal Assistance
Centre (LAC) has been awarded the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) Maurice Pate Award for 1997 for its work on children's
rights, reported the South African Press Association today.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the UNICEF in Windhoek, capital of
Namibia, said the LAC was selected from 13 nominations worldwide for
its work on the child care and protection act, the maintenance
act and its juvenile justice program.
</P>
<P>
"The LAC in Namibia plays a key role in lobbying for legal reforms
and has a wider importance to the Southern African region," said the
UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
Earlier recipients of Maurice Pate Award include the Pan-African
Institute for Development, the League of Red Cross and Red Crescent
Societies and the United Kingdom-based Child to Child Trust. enditem

