<HEADLINE> Yemeni President Confident of Free, Fair Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh
said here today that the upcoming parliamentary elections will be
free and democratic under international supervision despite a
planned boycott by the Opposition.
</P>
<P>
The president made the statement when meeting a team of
international observers who had come to Yemen to supervise the
parliamentary elections, due to take place on April 27.
</P>
<P>
According to the Yemeni news agency, Saleh affirmed during the
meeting that the Supreme Elections Committee and the related state
organs should offer support to the international observers, so
that the observers might move freely in all constituencies.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the elections would take place in secure
and reassuring climate, adding that the government has taken all
measures in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni president made it clear that observers might choose
the constituencies to supervise, in any province throughout the
country. The Supreme Election Committee has taken the necessary
security measures for the maintenance of order during the
elections, he said.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties earlier defied Yemeni authorities and urged
voters to boycott the upcoming elections. The parties called on
people to stay away from the elections and to hold mass protests.
</P>
<P>
In Aden, the stronghold of the Opposition, some 5,000 security
forces and hundreds of tanks have been deployed to prevent any
mishaps during balloting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
