<HEADLINE> African Leaders Urged to Help Rescue Children in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) today appealed to African leaders to use their influence
with Zairian rebel forces to ensure the care and protection of
refugee children and the immediate evacuation of the most
vulnerable unaccompanied children.
</P>
<P>
In a strong call for action issued here today, UNICEF Executive
Director Ms Carol Bellamy urged South African President Nelson
Mandela in particular to intercede directly with Laurent Kabila,
head of the Zairian rebel forces, the Alliance of Democratic
Forces for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"As the world watches and waits, hundreds of children are at
death's door," she said. "But food and medicine are close at hand.
These innocent children can be saved."
</P>
<P>
UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan has deplored recent attacks on
refugees and humanitarian workers in eastern Zaire and urged all
the parties to stop the fighting and allow the unimpeded delivery
of humanitarian assistance to the civilian population caught in
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
"I pay tribute to the courage of all the aid workers who, in
spite of extremely difficult conditions, are doing their utmost to
deliver assistance to the population in need," the
secretary-general said in a statement issued here Monday. "I hope
repatriation and air-bridge operations will start very soon to
save the lives of the vulnerable women and children needing better
care."
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, the UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)
called on the Kisangani authorities in eastern Zaire to take
urgent action to airlift Rwandan refugees home, saying that each
day's delay would lead to more deaths.
</P>
<P>
Since Friday, violence and looting have prevented relief
workers from conducting emergency programs for more than 100,000
malnourished and desperate refugees in the area and for
neighboring villages. "A series of security incidents, including
the looting of foodstocks, have blocked our access to the camps.
Today the military told us that we would not be allowed in the
camps because of a security operation in the area," High
Commissioner Ms Sadako Ogata said in a statement Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
