<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algerian Terrorists Massacre 93 Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Ninety-three Algerians were
massacred from Monday night to early this morning in a small
village near the the Algerian capital Algiers by a group of
Islamic extremists, the Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted Algerian
security forces as saying today.
</P>
<P>
AFP said that this is the biggest massacre of civilians by
Islamists ever made known by the Algerian government since
violence began ravaging the country in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The massacre took place in the village of Haouch Boughfi el
Khemisti, which is near Bougara and 25 kilometers south of
Algiers. The village is located on the plain of Mitidja, where the
militant Armed Islamic Group (GIA) is very active.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-two civilians, most of them women, were massacred last
week by Islamists on the same plain. Four women abducted by the
Islamists were later found raped and killed.
</P>
<P>
The latest massacre brought to 300 the number of civilians
killed in the regions of Blida and Medea south of Algiers since
April 3, said AFP quoting partial estimations.
</P>
<P>
Since November 1996, hundreds of villagers have been
slaughtered in Blida and Medea by Islamists who resorted to a way
of terror and atrocity in their killings -- cutting throats,
mutilating bodies, chopping off heads and slaughtering pregnant
women and their babies, sometimes with seesaws.
</P>
<P>
The GIA has claimed responsibility for several of the killings
in their underground publications.
</P>
<P>
The United States State Department said that 60,000 people have
been killed since 1992, after the Algerian army deprived the now
outlawed Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) party of a parliamentary
election victory.
</P>
<P>
Algeria will organize its legislative elections on June 5,
which will be participated in by most of the country's political
parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
