<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obscure Farmers Elected Village Chief by Self-Recommendation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- In a classroom of his village's
school, farmer Chen Huiting gave the first campaign speech of his
life.
</P>
<P>
Chen lives in Nanyuze, in Tunliu County of north China's Shanxi
Province. In this year's election of his village committee, the
village leadership, he recommended himself for candidacy and was
ultimately chosen as the group's director, or village chief.
</P>
<P>
Under Chinese law, candidates for the villagers' committees are
mainly nominated by the village branch of the Communist Party of
China, the villagers' electoral groups, or more than 10 villagers.
</P>
<P>
Self-recommendation is a new nomination practice that has
emerged in recent years. Eleven of the 18 candidates for the
villagers' committee in Nanyuze named themselves for consideration
as candidates.
</P>
<P>
"Self-recommendation has given obscure ordinary farmers the
chance to enter village leadership," said an official with the
local civil affairs department, which oversaw the election.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, China initiated direct elections for the villagers'
committees, held once every three years.
</P>
<P>
In the past election, candidates were mostly people who had
been village cadres before or enjoyed the respect of the villagers.
</P>
<P>
In the new round of elections that began in 1996, many villages
gave each eligible voter the right of self-nomination, as long as
he or she could obtain the signed support of at least 10 fellow
villagers.
</P>
<P>
This has helped a number of ordinary farmers, who are not
members of the Communist Party and never served as village cadres,
to become strong competitors for membership in the villagers'
committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
