However, Swanepoel said there were contingency plans for an
evacuation "if things go wrong". He could not confirm reports
that the South African air force had planes on eight-hour
stand-by to airlift citizens if necessary.
</P>
<P>
About 50 South Africans were known to be in Zaire one month ago,
and South African embassy officials were in contact with them,
Swanepoel said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Zairean reble forces led by Laurent Kabila
were preparing for the final offensive on Kinshasa, the capital of
Zaire, to seize power from ailing President Mobutu Sese Seko who has
ruled the country for 32 years. enditem

