<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obscure Farmers Elected Village Chief by Self-Recommendation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We farmers were used to accepting anyone appointed as village
cadres by governments at higher level," said a Nanyuze villager.
"Now things are different. If you want to work for the people, you
must first let them know you."
</P>
<P>
Before the preliminary election that decided formal candidates,
each of the 18 candidates of Nanyuze gave a campaign speech to the
villagers' delegates in the village school.
</P>
<P>
They must answer three questions: Why do you want to become a
village cadre? What do you plan to do for the village if you are
elected? What will happen if you lose the election?
</P>
<P>
All the speeches were recorded, then broadcast to the entire
village for two days.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who is self-employed as a tractor driver, clinched the
final election for village chief with a successful speech, beating
out his rival, who was nominated by the village Party branch, by a
slim margin.
</P>
<P>
"The election was just like a fair examination," Chen
said. "The new nomination method of self-recommendation enabled me
to join it."
</P>
<P>
Cui Kexue, another self-recommended candidate, was not as
lucky: he received only one vote of support in the preliminary
election.
</P>
<P>
"I failed because most villagers didn't understand me," Cui
said. "The election speeches should be made on the streets,
instead of in a classroom."
</P>
<P>
Guo Xiaoping, vice director of the Shanxi Provincial Department
of Civil Affairs, said that no matter which method of nomination
is adopted, only those candidates whom the people are willing to
choose could win the election.
</P>
<P>
"An open and fair village election will help maintain the
stability of the rural political power at the grassroots level,"
he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
