<HEADLINE> Gujral Wins Vote of Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- I.K. Gujral, who was sworn in
as India's 12th prime minister Monday, won a vote of confidence
this evening in the Lower House after more than 10 hours of
debate.
</P>
<P>
The vote of confidence was passed by a voice vote.
</P>
<P>
Indian President S.D. Sharma appointed Gujral as prime minister
on April 20 and asked him to prove his majority in the Lower House
on April 22.
</P>
<P>
Gujral, a former foreign minister in the Gowda government, was
elected leader of the 13-party United Front to replace Deve Gowda,
who was disliked by the Congress party, supporter of the United
Front.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party criticized the Gowda government for its
failure to contain the "communal forces" and strengthen "secular
forces" in the past 10 months and insisted that the United Front
should change its leader so as to get back support of the Congress
party, which withdrew its support to the Gowda government on March
30.
</P>
<P>
Gujral today promised to seek consensus in solving all problems
in the country and to try his best to deepen and widen the
economic reform process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
