<HEADLINE> Irish Businessman Admits Giving Former PM Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Irish businessman Ben Dunne told
an official tribunal on payments to politicians in Dublin today
that he personally gave former Irish Prime Minister Charles
Haughey 200,000 pounds (about 320,000 U.S. dollars), said reports
from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Dunne told the tribunal that he gave Haughey, who had been
Irish prime minister between 1979 and 1992, the money in the form
of three bank drafts of about 70,000 pounds (about 112,000
dollars) each in 1991.
</P>
<P>
But he made it clear that he never expected "any favor or
benefit" from Haughey, one of the most powerful figures in Irish
politics for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
Dunne, former head of the Irish Dunne's department store chain,
said that he understood that Haughey owed about 1 million pounds
(about 1.6 million dollars) and he gave him the money to help ease
the debts.
</P>
<P>
Dennis McCulough, counsel for the tribunal, said Monday that
Dunne handed over from 1987 to 1991 a total of 1.3 million pounds
(about 2 million dollars) to Haughey, who has denied receiving any
money in a letter to the judge overseeing the hearing.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal is expected to last for at least a few weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
