<HEADLINE> Iraqi Helicopters fly No-fly Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi helicopters, bringing back
pilgrims home from mecca, entered the no-fly zone in the south and
landed safely this morning at the Iraqi-Saudi border area of
Ar'ar, about 350 kilometers southwest of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iraqi news agency INA, Iraqi government sent
at least seven military helicopters Tuesday to pick up Iraqi pilgrims
who went to mecca by air to perform Hajj earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters took off from Al-Taji military base on the
northern outskirts of the capital city Baghdad and dozens of Iraqi
and foreign journalists were invited on board.
</P>
<P>
This move was made in defiance of the air-traffic ban imposed
on Iraq in 1991 by the allied forces after the Gulf war. According
to the report, despite the U.S. warnings, the Iraqi helicopters
entered the no-fly zone patrolled by the U.S. air force.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi government spokesman Monday warned the U.S. that any
hostile action could threaten the safety of Iraqi pilgrims, and be
faced with "appropriate reaction" from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman also said it is Iraq's legitimate right to
use its civilian aircraft to fly home the Iraqi pilgrims from
Mecca.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. in turn has warned that Iraq would face unspecified
retaliation for the action. A White House spokesman stated Monday
that his country will not shot down the Iraqi helicopters, adding
that the U.S. "would respond appropriately."
</P>
<P>
On April 9, defying the air embargo, an Iraqi passenger plane
flew 104 elderly and sick Muslims to Saudi Arabia for Hajj, one of
five essential obligations of Islam for its believers. The plane
flew to Saudi Arabia via Jordan to avoid the no-fly zone in
southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. insisted that the flight violated U.N. resolutions,
but it failed to press the UN Security Council to pass a
statement to condemn Iraq for the flight.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi government said earlier that relevant UN resolutions,
namely 661 and 670 have not banned the use by Iraq of its
airplanes outside its borders.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also said it strongly rejects any new interpretation
of UN resolutions 661 and 670 as well as other resolutions.
it will preserve the right to use its airliners.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had appealed to UN Security Council several times this
year to allow it to fly Iraqi pilgrims to Mecca, but the request
was rejected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
