<HEADLINE> Zairean Rebels Urged to Ensure Safe Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
today called on Zairean rebels "to ensure a secure environment in
which aid can be safely delivered".
</P>
<P>
In a news flash issued here today, the WFP said that late
Tuesday afternoon, the entire load of relief food on a train en
route to the refugee camps was looted by Zairean villagers.
</P>
<P>
About 119 tons of relief food were stolen out of a total of
120 tons aboard the train during a violent overnight attack seven
kilometers from Kisangani, the third largest city of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
A further 72 tons of food were stolen overnight Sunday by the
local people from a WFP depot in Kasese Town, 25 kilometers south
of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
Catherine Bertini, WFP Executive Director, strongly deplored
the theft of some 200 tons of relief food from a WFP train and
depot in the Kisangani area.
</P>
<P>
He said that "we've been working flat out to feed people and
to save thousands of lives in these camps. This is a terrible
loss. Desperately hungry people are reliant on that very food
for their survival."
</P>
<P>
According to the news flash, the events have not only resulted
in a loss of more than 500,000 U.S. Dollars worth of food and
supplies, but have caused a total blockade of all aid assistance
to the camps in eastern Zaire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
