<HEADLINE> Malaysian Foreign Minister Concludes Visit to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister Ahmad
Badawi concluded his five-day visit to Iraq designed to promote
trade and economic relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Badawi held talks with president Saddam
Hussein and Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz and several government
ministers.
</P>
<P>
The talks centered on how to promote trade and economic ties
as well as "open up new horizons" for increasing trade volume
between Iraq and Malaysia, according to the Iraqi News Agency
(INA).
</P>
<P>
During a meeting on Sunday, Aziz briefed Badawi on Iraq's
relation with the UN Security Council, saying Iraq has met all
its commitments to relevant UN resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized the "intransigent position" of the U.S.
and its hostile attitude toward his country, which have
"dubious political aims that have nothing to do with Security
Council resolutions".
</P>
<P>
INA quoted Badawi as stressing that he has probed with the
Iraqi side the best means to better bilateral cooperation in
all fields, but gave no details of the cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian foreign minister and his delegation arrived in
Baghdad on Friday and left for home this morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
