<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Constroversial Egyptian-Israeli Project Needs More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The controversial and expensive
Midor oil refinery project, which brings together Egyptian and
Israeli private businessmen in partnership with the Egyptian
government, is seeking more international equity.
</P>
<P>
Repsol of Spain and Agip of Italy are interested in taking
shares in the big project, Egyptian Oil Minister Hamdy al-Banbi
told a press conference today.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot predict how much shares (they will take) and when
the contract will be finalized because it is their chance, but I
welcome them to join (the project)," he said.
</P>
<P>
And if they fail to come up, shares will be offered to the
public to further the privatization process in the oil sector as
well, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
When plans for the refinery were first announced two years
ago, the project made headlines as an example of the new links
possible between Egyptian and Israeli businessmen as a result of
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In the original plan, the Swiss Merhav and Irish Midor, which
group some Israeli and Egyptian private businessmen, each had a 40
percent share holding in the one-billion-U.S.-dollar project.
</P>
<P>
But serious financial problems almost derailed it in January
until the oil ministry decided the state-owned Egyptian General
Petroleum Corp (EGPC) should move up its share from 20 percent to
60 percent and increase its capital investment from 200 million
to 600 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, Merhav and Midor each hold 20 percent now.
</P>
<P>
Banbi said the contract is being finalized and discussions are
going on, but he set no deadline for the operation.
</P>
<P>
Turning to an even more controversial Israeli-Egyptian gas
network, the so-called Peace Pipeline, Banbi said the project is
"in a standstill," for "technical reasons."
</P>
<P>
Describing the project as an overblown case of propaganda,
Banbi said it is actually a "very small project," that has "little
economic repercussions."
</P>
<P>
Egypt does "not give it a big priority," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to make peace with Israel but
the bilateral ties have been cool because of the deteriorating
peace prospects in the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Cabinet Approves Tax Reform Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The German cabinet today approved a
comprehensive tax reform plan which would produce a net annual tax
reduction of 30 billion marks, or 17.6 billion U.S. dollars, for
the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
The tax reform plan, proposed by Finance Minister Theo Waigel,
is believed to be the country's biggest tax-revision package since
1949. Aiming at bolstering business confidence, investment and
hiring, it has become the government's top domestic policy
priority and its main recipe to curb record high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
But the Bonn government still needs to strike a compromise on
the tax reform plan with the main opposition Social Democratic
Party (SPD) if the plan is to survive the upper house of the
German parliament, Bundesrat, where the SPD controls a majority.
</P>
<P>
Under the package, the government wants, among other things, to
cut income taxes to 15 percent for low-wage earners and 39 percent
for people with high incomes instead of the current marginal rates
ranging from 25.9 percent to 53 percent. Business revenue tax
would also be axed from 47 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
This would lead to a shortfall of 82 billion marks (48 billion
dollars) in state revenues, 38 billion (22 billion dollars) of
which would be recouped by eliminating tax loopholes and
write-offs, the government says.
</P>
<P>
Of the remaining 44 billion mark (26 billion dollar) shortfall
the government says it would recoup a further 14 billion marks
(8 billion dollars) by boosting consumption taxes, probably by
raising value added tax (VAT) by one percentage point to 16
percent.
</P>
<P>
This would leave the public with 30 billion marks in net annual
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
The SPD, however, has spoken in favor of keeping the top income
rate at 53 percent or trimming it only modestly, a strategy meant
to keep the tax burden on those best suited to pay.
</P>
<P>
It also accuses the government of playing down the financial
shortfall which would be induced by tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the SPD and the government have held three rounds of
tax negotiations since February 26, all failed to make headway.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and SPD leader Oskar Lafontaine are
scheduled to meet Wednesday in Bonn to try to seek a compromise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
