<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sustainable Agricultural Development Urged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA) today stressed the importance of
transforming Africa's agricultural sector into a state that is
productive and sustainable.
</P>
<P>
ECA Executive Secretary K. Y. Amoako made the remarks here
when he was opening a high level expert meeting jointly organized
by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) and the ECA on
capacity building for food security and sustainable agricultural
development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Amoako said the meeting was held "at a time of great concern
that many Africans still do not have economic access to
sufficient, safe and nutritious food to meet their dietary needs
and food preferences for an active and healthy life."
</P>
<P>
It was held also "at a time of great promise for addressing
the food insecurity and sustainable agricultural development
problems of Africa," he added.
</P>
<P>
He told the participants to focus their deliberations on four
areas: market deregulation, agricultural sustainability, income
generation and diversification, and trade, cooperation and
integration.
</P>
<P>
According to the organizers of the meeting, the overall
objective of the four-day workshop is to lay out a "road map"
that will enable UNDP and ECA to help strengthen capacities for
planning and managing interventions in support of food security
and sustainable agricultural development at the national,
sub-regional, and regional levels in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from African countries, United Nations
agencies and international organizations attended the first day
of the meeting. 
</P>
