<HEADLINE> West Urged to Be Neutral on Kenya's Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
today urged western donors to be neutral on Kenya's political
issues and asked them to write off some of the country's debts.
</P>
<P>
The president was speaking here today when he received 40
lorries donated by the Japanese government for transport of
relief supplies in the country.
</P>
<P>
He wondered why certain western countries who said they were
for democracy failed to condemn and even supported violence in
Africa, adding that some countries wished to push Kenya to the
brink of civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan leader stressed that western countries did not
understand fully the root cause of problems affecting Africa.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that developed countries had social welfare
systems to look after their unemployed citizens while African
countries could not support such arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the constitutional changes in Kenya, he said that
his government's cautious approach to the problem was to
forestall upheavals inherent in careless amendments.
</P>
<P>
Moi noted that any meaningful change in Kenya's constitution
needed serious discussions because it affected all Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that any sudden change in the constitution
could cause chaos, jeopardize the process of democratization and
scare away investors. 
</P>
