<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Adjusts War Game Plan for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has adjusted the plan of
joint military exercises with Greece to make them less sensitive
for the sake of the ongoing proximity talks between the Greek and
Turkish communities, an official spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a cabinet meeting here, Government
Spokesman Manolis Christofides said Greek fighters will not fly
within Cyprus' air space during the proximity talks.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, however, stressed that this decision was not
taken under pressure but is a good-will gesture indicating the
government's determination to proceed with the ongoing proximity
talks between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"Following a proposal by President Glafcos Clerides and after
consultations between the governments of Greece and Cyprus, it
was said that part of a military exercise "Vergina", dealing
with the interception of hostile aircraft can also take place
outside Cyprus' air space," Christofides said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that maneuvers to counter an offensive by enemy
planes attacking land targets in Cyprus "is to be postponed at
present."
</P>
<P>
Christofides said the Cypriot army exercises "Toxotis" with
the participation of the Greek military, "will take place in
close proximity to Cyprus but not within its territorial
waters."
</P>
<P>
At the end of these exercises, and with the consent of the
Cypriot government, Greek navy vessels will visit Cyprus in an
official capacity, he added.
</P>
<P>
"President Clerides and Greek Premier Costas Simitis share
the belief that during the proximity talks, it would be good not
to have Greek fighter planes flying in Cyprus' air space,"
Christofides told the press.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece signed a joint defense pact in November
1993, which provides for joint military exercises between the
two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
He said Foreign Minister Yiannakis Cassoulides has already
informed the U.N. and other interested countries about the
government's decision.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led proximity talks, which began on March 10, were
conducted by the U.N. Resident Representative Gustave Feissel,
who had bi-weekly separate meetings with President Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
The talks are aimed at paving the way for the U.N. proposed
face-to-face negotiations between leaders of the two communities
by the middle of this year, and getting the two sides to adopt
good-will gestures to create a positive climate for the direct
talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright (the then
U.S. ambassador to the U.N.) first proposed a ban on overflights
by Greek and Turkish aircraft over Cyprus last year, but the idea
was rejected by the Greek Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island has remained divided since
1974 when Turkish troops occupied the northern third in the wake
of an Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
