<HEADLINE> Iran to Build More Railways to Revive Silk Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government declared
here today that it plans to build two new railway lines to
connect the Indian subcontinent to the west, north and south via
Iran.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani
in his letter to the opening ceremony of the four-day Second
International Conference on the Silk Road, which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani said that Iran has revived the Silk Road by
constructing long rail lines starting from the Gulf and stretching
to Sarakhs, a border town near Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president said that Iran is trying to attract the
attention of tourists to the Iranian Islamic civilization by
exerting efforts on the day-to-day development of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Silk Road, more than 7,000 kilometers in length, snakes
through nine key countries, including China, nations of the
Commonwealth of Independent States, Afghanistan, Iran, Iraq and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
Eduardo Ramos, representative of the World Tourism
Organization, said at the meeting that the WTO will fully support
the Silk Road project which started in China in 1994.
</P>
<P>
He said that the tourism organization will present a report on
the WTO's activities and a future program for promoting tourism
along the Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
Xue Fan, representative of the China National Tourism
Administration, said that the Silk Road project has attracted
more and more tourists from various countries of the world.
</P>
<P>
She said that China has accommodated many tourists groups.
However, the transportation still remains a headache for further
development, she added.
</P>
<P>
Deborah Luhrman, press attache of the WTO, said that China has
contributed a lot to the tourism project of the Silk Road,
claiming that China, in fact, is what she called a teacher for
some CIS nations since it has had good infrastructure such as
hotels and tourist services.
</P>
<P>
She said that her organization is trying its best to
facilitate the Silks Road project by facilitating visa
procedures and updating information of airlines and hotels.
</P>
<P>
Luhrman said the objective for the meeting is to "bring
together all government officials in different countries,"
especially the nations along the Silk Road, to "explore ways" to
promote tourism along the Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 representatives from the World Tourism Organization,
the United Nations including the U.N. Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization (UNESCO) and delegates from 23 countries
are attending the congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
