<HEADLINE> General Meeting of Ethiopian Workers Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The 8th general meeting of
Ethiopian workers today called for re-establishing the
Confederation of Ethiopian Trade Unions (CETU).
</P>
<P>
Opening the three-day congress, Ethiopian Minister of Labor
and Social Affairs Hassan Abdella urged the CETU new leadership
to organize members with the aim of developing the national
economy and struggling for the rights and benefits of its
members.
</P>
<P>
He said the workers and the society at large are expected to
resist certain hardships and strive for the achievement of
sustainable and durable prosperity under the five-year
development program.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the coordinating committee for the
re-establishment of CETU, Aregawi Kebede, said the confederation
is expected to elect leaders free of any influence in a bid to
bring industrial peace conductive to the economic development of
the country.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his belief that a reorganized CETU will defend
the interest of the workers by strengthening its unison with the
aim of alleviating the problems of members.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the International Labor Organization (ILO)
said the ILO is ready to recognize and support the new CETU.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the meeting, representing over 95 percent of
the workers under eight trade unions federations, are expected to
elect their leaders and audit committee members in addition to
approving the new statute and code of ethics.
</P>
<P>
The CETU has now 503 member trade unions. 
</P>
