<HEADLINE> Clinton Views Flooded Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
flew over the flood devastation from the swollen Red River in
Grand Forks of North Dakota, and East Grand Forks in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
"We'll do what we have to do," news reports quoted Clinton as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Most of us can't imagine facing a fire, a flood and a blizzard
all at the same time. I've never seen a community this inundated
with floods," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Looking down from the helicopter, Clinton said, "Every one of
those houses is a life story."
</P>
<P>
With estimates of 1 billion dollars or more in damage, Clinton
announced he would ask Congress for an additional 200 million
dollars in emergency funds for North Dakota, South Dakota and
Minnesota. The three states already have been allotted 288 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Federal Emergency Management Agency would
reimburse 100 percent of the cost for immediate emergency work
rather than the usual 75 percent and added 18 counties in
Minnesota and 53 in South Dakota to those eligible for disaster
relief.
</P>
<P>
Clinton already has declared disasters in 149 counties in the
three states and officials expect the number to keep rising.
</P>
</TEXT>
