<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Maintains Ban on Imports of Cows from Some </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian Minister of
Agriculture Mijhim Khreishah today reiterated the ban on import of
live cows, meat and dairy products from any country where the
mad-cow disease appears.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian Minister made this statement during his meeting
with a specialized French delegation representing the Ministries
of Agriculture, Finance and Economy in France.
</P>
<P>
The French team is visiting Jordan to portray the facts
relating to the detection of cases of mad-cow disease which has
prompted Jordan to ban the import of cows and dairy products from
France.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian news agency (Petra) has quoted the Jordanian
Minister as saying that Jordan will under no circumstances allow
any such imports unless it is positively certain that the foreign
exporting country is free of that epidemic and its cows absolutely
safe.
</P>
<P>
The two sides exchanged views during the meeting about
technical topics and details related to the mad-cow disease, the
follow-up of cows' health conditions, and the kind of fodder and
food provided to cows.
</P>
<P>
On their part, the French delegation members pointed out that
only 18 cases of mad-cow disease have been reported in France
since 1991, whereas, the number of cows throughout France is
approximately 20 million.
</P>
<P>
The delegation asserted that all cows in the country are
subject to health control since their birth, that each cow has
certified birth and health certificates, and that export of cows
and related products will take place after ascertaining their safety.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian Minister promised to convey the French views to
the competent Jordanian authorities to study and to adopt the
necessary measures in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Jordan imports the greater part of its needs of live cows,
frozen meats and dairy products from abroad. At present it imports
most cows and frozen meat from Australia and India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
