<HEADLINE> Serbs Harassed in Croat-Controlled Area: IPTF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Serbs continue being harassed in
Drvar, a western Bosnian area where they used to be the majority
and which is now controlled by Croats, the UN said today.
</P>
<P>
According to Alexander Ivanko, a spokesman for the UN
International Task Force (IPTF), A "very ugly incident" was
reported in Drvar Sunday, in which a house belonging to a Serb
female was set on fire.
</P>
<P>
When she tried to put out the fire, the suspects fire in the
air to frighten her, Ivanko said.
</P>
<P>
Although local police have reported the incident to the IPTF
and are currently investigating, it represented "the continued
policy of harassment of a small minority of Serbs still living in
the Drvar area," Ivanko said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the local Serbs fled their homes in late 1995 when the
Serb forces, which earlier had an upper hand, was routed by
Croatian troops. 
