<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Official on Proposed Zairean Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Zairean rebel leader
Laurent Kabila has reiterated his commitment to the proposed
direct talks with Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko in South
Africa later this week, a South African senior official said
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Assembly's Foreign Affairs Committee
in Cape Town, South African Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad
said the South African government is still awaiting the official
confirmation from Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
Pahad was apparently referring to President Nelson Mandela's
formal invitation to Mobutu, delivered by Mobutu's special envoy
Honore Nganda last Thursday, to meet Kabila in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Although Mobutu has since indicated publicly that he would
agree to "talks in principle", he has yet to formally reply to
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
"When we get an official response, we will inform everybody
what the real truth is," said Pahad.
</P>
<P>
Statements by Mobutu's son and spokesman Nzanga Mobutu
indicated that his 66-year-old ailing father was not willing to
meet his foe in South Africa because of his ill health, and was
proposing another venue for the talks.
</P>
<P>
However, it is not clear whether the rebels would accept a new
venue for the first face-to-face talks between Mobutu and Kabila
since the breakout of the civil war in October last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
