<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian PM Predicts Upsurge in Cooperation with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri said today that the coming period will witness an
upsurge in Egyptian economic cooperation with Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival at the Cairo Airport from his ten-day Asian trip,
the premier made the remarks, summing up his full-agenda visit to
Singapore, Malaysia and China as very "fruitful."
</P>
<P>
"The trip will give a boost to joint ventures and Egyptian
exports to Asian countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri spoke highly of China's economic reform and
development program, saying that he was impressed by the great
changes China has been going through.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen special economic zone and Pudong New District in
Shanghai offer a good example for Egypt in establishing free
economic zones, Ganzouri said. "We hope to work with China in
this respect," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian premier told Xinhua that he held talks with
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, Premier Li Peng and Vice-Premier
Zhu Rongji to explore the prospects for economic, trade and
political cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"The immediate outcome (of the trip to China) takes form in
the Sino-Egyptian free trade zone in Suez and a series of
investment projects," he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, the Egyptian prime minister signed an accord on
preparing joint feasibility studies with China for a free trade
zone in north of the Gulf of Suez. Egyptian businessmen and their
Chinese counterparts signed 11 deals and accords for joint
industrial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Egypt also concluded four cooperation accords with Malaysia,
and an agreement on investment protection and promotion as well a
trade pact with Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri is the first Egyptian Prime Minister to visit China
since the two countries established diplomatic ties in 1956.
</P>
</TEXT>
