<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Opposes European Integration, Devolution for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) - British Prime Minister John Major
said today he was opposed to closer European integration just as
he was against devolution for Scotland.
</P>
<P>
In an election campaign tour to Scotland, Major said that
because the European Union wants Europe's states to break up into
regions, any further transfer of power to the European Union
risked cutting Scotland adrift from the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to win the fifth term of office in Downing Street,
Major said the task of his Conservative party would be to ensure
that Britain "doesn't sink itself into a Europe of the regions" if
the party wins again in the May 1 election.
</P>
<P>
"A centralist, federalist Europe with more authority taken away
from the Westminster parliament and handed to the European
parliament and the Commission and others in Brussels," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also attacked the opposition Labor party's plans to set up a
parliament in Scotland with tax-raising powers and warned that it
was bound to lead to conflict with the parliament in London and
thence to independence for Scotland.
</P>
<P>
"Understand that point! Baldly and in the most straightforward
fashion I say it: the devolutionary proposals of our political
opponents are the first step on the route that inevitably will
lead -- I cannot tell you how soon -- to the break-up of the
United Kingdom as we at present know it," he underlined.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Major also exchanged arguments with Labor leader Tony
Blair over who would best defend Britain in Europe, after a
surprise intervention by EU Commission head Jacques Santer.
</P>
<P>
Santer on Monday attacked Eurosceptic "doom merchants" and
insisted European states should move towards closer integration.
</P>
</TEXT>
