<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Officials on Greek-Turkish Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos said today that a proposed Greek-Turkish committee of
experts would be of a "strictly procedural nature" and its
objective would be to ascertain whether there were
misunderstandings on each side and to facilitate the procedure
which might possibly arise.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after briefing the main opposition New
Democracy (ND) party leader on foreign policy issues, Pangalos
stressed that political will was required on the part of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He added that Athens intended to pursue with all means possible
the settlement of problems within generally accepted frameworks
such as international law, the International Court at the Hague,
respect for peace and refraining from the use of force.
</P>
<P>
ND leader Costas Karamanlis voiced concern and reservations
about the framework and content of the government handling with
respect to the proposed committee of experts.
</P>
<P>
Karamanlis said that his party would closely watch the
developments and impede any handling by the Greek government which
was not in the nation's best interests and led to increased
tension in Greek-Turkish ties.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, commenting on the formation of the committee of
experts, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said later
today that "the ball is in the court of the Dutch presidency" of
the European Union (EU) following Greece's approval and prior to
the reply expected from Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Reppas said that if the committee was formed, it could conclude
with findings which, however, would not be binding on either the
Greek or Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties recently accused the socialist PASOK
government of exercising "secret diplomacy" and entering into a
"dialogue" with Turkey with "unforeseeable consequences."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis and his
government also was reportedly caught up in a bitter exchange with
32 Ruling PASOK deputies who warned that the government was
"slipping" into a dialogue with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
They threatened to jeopardize the Simitis-led government's
majority in the Greek parliament by withdrawing their support if
this turned out to be true. 
</P>
</TEXT>
