<HEADLINE> U.S. Chrysler Engine Plant Strike Affects 16 Factories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- About 23,000 Chrysler Corp.
workers in 16 North American factories were idle as a result of an
engine plant strike which entered its 12th day today.
</P>
<P>
The latest layoffs came at parts plants in Michigan and Indiana
of the United States and two pickup truck assembly plants in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen Chrysler plants in the United States, Canada and Mexico
have been affected, including the engine plant in Detroit where
1,800 workers kicked off the strike April 10.
</P>
<P>
The strike has affected North American production of the U.S.
No. 3 auto-maker's highly profitable Dodge Ram and Dakota pickups
and Jeep Grand Cherokee sport utility vehicles. It also has
stopped production of the Dodge Viper sports car and Dodge Ram
vans.
</P>
<P>
Pickup assembly lines in Lago Alberto and Saltillo in
neighboring Mexico shut down last week and workers were informed
Monday they were laid off indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
High-level talks continued in Detroit on Monday for ending the
strike which was staged for protesting against the company's
outsourcing and other issues. Chrysler was refusing to back down
on its right to farm out 300 jobs covered by the United Auto
Workers (UAW) union to an independent supplier.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations also reportedly continued in a 17-day strike at
the No. 1 automaker General Motors Corp. assembly plant in
Oklahoma City, where long hours are the top issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 12,000 workers at Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co. plants
in seven states remained on strike over wages, outsourcing and
other issues. Negotiators for the tire company and the United
Steelworkers of America were to resume their talks today, the
third day of the strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
