<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Rebels to Continue Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) today agreed to
continue their talks amid sporadic armed conflicts between the
military and MILF rebels in Mindanao island, the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Lawyer Lanang Ali, head of the MILF cessation committee, told
reporters that this agreement was reached when the two sides met
today to begin their two-day third round peace talks in Catobato
city in Maguindanao province.
</P>
<P>
Ali said the cessation committees of two sides would also try
to forge a general ceasefire agreement before their meeting ends
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying our best to come up with solutions because we
came here for peace," Ali said. But he declined to give more
details.
</P>
<P>
He said the Manila-MILF joint-committee is due to release a
joint statement on the result of their discussions Thursday,
according to the Philippine News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The government troops and the MILF have been engaged in
sporadic fighting in some areas of Mindanao island since early
last week, killing at least 27 people.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government had signed a peace deal with the
mainstream Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) last September,
ending nearly three decades of war between the MNLF and the
government troops in the south.
</P>
<P>
The government also wanted to forge a peace deal with the MILF,
which refused to accept the Manila-MNLF peace accord and has
sought to establish an independent Islamic state.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
