<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Urge Early Notification of Handover Events </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Organizers of public events to
mark the handover were advised today to notify the police of their
plans as early as possible so as to ensure minimum inconvenience
to the public.
</P>
<P>
The Police Planning and Implementation Team, which acts as the
link between the organizing bodies and the police, will discuss
with the organizers measures which will take into consideration
the interests of the organizers themselves, the participants and
the public.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference today, Lee Ming-kwai, assistant
commissioner of police (special duties) and also head of the team,
said the unprecedented nature of the handover would most likely
attract organizations or individuals to hold public events.
</P>
<P>
"While the police respect individuals' rights to gather, to
celebrate or to express views, we have to ensure that public
safety and public order are maintained," Lee noted.
</P>
<P>
"We are aware of about 180 celebratory events to be held by
various organizations in June and July this year. They include
fireworks displays, float parades, carnivals, variety shows,
concerts and banquets," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I would urge organizers of public events to notify us early
and furnish details so that police can make necessary arrangements
to facilitate the events," he added.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Lee revealed that a security cordon will be
gradually put in place starting from June 26 to encompass the East
Tamar site, where a farewell ceremony will be held around sunset
on June 30 and the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center
Extension, the venue of a gala banquet on that evening and a
handover ceremony at midnight.
</P>
<P>
There will also be traffic diversions on a few nearby roads.
</P>
<P>
"Our plan is to designate the two sites as a secure zone," he
said. "Any staff, guests or press entering the secure area will
have to go through screening."
</P>
<P>
He assured that the police are adequately trained and
well-geared for the exercise.
</P>
<P>
"We have started a series of training programs which include
study visits to various major international events and overseas
security courses," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
"Special courses are being conducted to boost the search and
VIP protection capability. Acquisition of X-ray machines, metal
detector archways and explosive detectors has already started.
Training for search dogs and handlers has strengthened," Lee
added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong police are responsible for all the security
arrangements of the handover and related particulars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
