<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Profile Economic Studies Map Out HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong needs to strengthen
the technology know-how of its manufacturing industry to maintain
a diversified economic base, and refine the port development
policy to enable integration with regional ports, suggested
leading local economists.
</P>
<P>
The Better Hong Kong Foundation and the Hong Kong Center for
Economic Research today released the findings of the first three
studies of a far-reaching research project on Hong Kong's social
and economic development in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The studies were commissioned by the Foundation and coordinated
by the Center. It involved economists from Hong Kong's leading
tertiary institutions for the first time in public issues.
</P>
<P>
The goal is to produce research that will make a contribution
to the continuing evolution of Hong Kong's economy and complement
the Hong Kong government's current initiatives in reviewing the
established policy in various areas, such as economic development
and old age services, said Henry Cheng, Advisory Council Chairman
of the Foundation.
</P>
<P>
And the studies will be made available to the Hong Kong
government and SAR government and other relevant parties, she
said.
</P>
<P>
The economic studies released today reinforce the Foundation's
commitment to encourage the strategic debate on how Hong Kong
should evolve as a financial, trading and business center in the
years to come, said Leonie Ki, Chief Executive of the Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The studies examined the role of technology and industry in
Hong Kong, trade and investment flows between China's mainland,
Hong Kong and Taiwan, and port facilities and container handling
services.
</P>
<P>
The studies were conducted by Associate Professor of the
Department of Economics of Chinese University Kwong Kai Sun,
Associate Professor of the University of Hong Kong K.C. Fung, Head
of the Department of Economics at Hong Kong University of Science
and Technology Professor Leonard Cheng and Professor of School of
Economics and Finance of the University of Hong Kong Richard Wong.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
