<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Predicts High GDP Growth in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is set to register real
GDP growth of 5.4 percent in 1997 and six in 1998 as against 4.4
and 4.7 percent achieved in 1995 and 1996 respectively, a country
projection report of the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The report said if the steps, taken up under the reform
programs of the present government after its assumption of office
in June 1996, are carried out properly, the country's economic
performance would register the above GDP (gross domestic products)
growth in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Under the reform programs, the government has taken steps to
restore macroeconomic stability and renew efforts at structural
reform including further privatization of state-owned enterprises
and strengthening implementation of external assistance projects.
</P>
<P>
Giving an elaborate account of the reform programs, the report
said the government has identified over 50 state-owned enterprises
including textile factories, sugar mills, chemical works and steel
plants for privatization by the middle of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the industrial sector began to make quick recovery
in the last quarter of 1996 after a major slow down, said the
report, adding that the growth of this sector is likely to be
seven percent in 1997 and 9.5 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the agricultural sector, the country is set to improve
long-term prospects, the report said, adding that the sector would
expand by over two percent in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Giving a brief account of the country's external trade and
payments, the report said in the next two years, more robust
exports at 14.5 percent and 16.6 percent in 1997 and 1998
respectively will be possible.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Bangladesh's problems and prospects as it
approaches the next century, the report said the main challenges
will be to reduce poverty and improve the living conditions of
people.
</P>
<P>
To make progress in these fields, the GDP growth must be
accelerated and the provision of social services also should be
enhanced, especially in terms of availability to the poor and the
disadvantaged, the report observed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
