<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Police Crack a Number of Drug-Related Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese police have reported a
series of successes since the beginning of a new round of targeted
action against narcotics-related crimes, which was kicked off
earlier this month, the Ministry of Public Security announced
today.
</P>
<P>
In north China's Shanxi Province, Li Xiangmin, wanted for the
past eight years on drug trafficking charges and worth 10,000 yuan
(about 1,200 U.S. dollars) of police reward for his capture, was
captured on April 1. In the city of Datong alone, 50 narcotics
crimes were solved and 64 suspects arrested.
</P>
<P>
On April 15, a major trans-province crime ring involved in drug
trafficking was broken up in Chongqing, with six suspects caught,
and 3,331 grams of heroin and 300,000 yuan of drug money retrieved.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, an 11-member drug trafficking gang was apprehended
by police, together with 5,800 grams of heroin.
</P>
<P>
In Yunnan, where drug-related crimes are especially common due
to its location near the notorious "Golden Triangle" of Burma,
Laos and Thailand, 588 kgs of heroin was captured in the first
three months this year.
</P>
<P>
A drug known as MDMA and MDA, an amphetamine nicknamed by the
Chinese as the "shaking head pill," has appeared in some urban
recreational centers in China, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The drug stimulates the nervous system, causing users to become
sexually excited and shake their heads violently. It is dangerous
to health and harmful to social stability, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Such pills have been uncovered in Shanghai, Shenyang and
Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The current targeted fight will continue through the end of
September, the ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
