<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Launches New Policy on Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
executive body of the European Union (EU), today launched a
strategy aimed at closer ties with Hong Kong in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
Far from being a time to downgrade links with the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China, the commission said,
1997 must mark another step forward in the relationship.
</P>
<P>
China will resume exercising the sovereignty of Hong Kong on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to developing close relations with the
Hong Kong SAR...to ensure that Hong Kong cements its place as one
of our most important Asian partners," said EU Trade Commissioner
Sir Leon Brittan.
</P>
<P>
The EU strategy emphasizes the importance of Hong Kong to the
evolution of relations in Asia as a whole.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for the 15-member European economic alliance to
produce a full annual report on EU-Hong Kong relations, including
commerce, finance and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The commission was confident that free access to the EU would
be in the interests of both the EU and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the EU's 10th largest trading partner, and home to
over 100 financial services companies, 100 manufacturers and the
regional headquarters of some 250 companies with EU origins.
</P>
</TEXT>
