<HEADLINE> Jordanian King, Arafat Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan and
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat had a
meeting today on the Middle East peace in the southern Jordanian
city of Aqaba.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said Arafat briefed the Jordanian monarch
on the outcome of the recent Palestinian talks with senior
U.S. officials, and his meeting with Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy on the sidelines of the recent Malta
European-Mediterranean partnership conference last week.
</P>
<P>
Hussein reiterated during the meeting Jordan's support for the
Palestinian people's struggle to obtain their legitimate rights
over their national territory.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the two leaders spelled out the necessity of
maintaining coordination in the coming stage, and the need to join
hands with regional and international forces to push forward the
peace process and bring it back on track.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also stressed the importance of removing the
obstacles that hinder the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Aqaba for a few hours' stop at noon today,
and left there in the afternoon right after the talks ended.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's visit to Jordan came within the context of
consultatons and coordination between the Jordanian and
Palestinian leaders, and the Palestinian president also expressed
his good wishes to Hussein who has just recovered from an
operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
