<HEADLINE> Smuggling Hits Tanning Industry in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's tanning industry is
likely to face dire consequences due to an acute shortage of raw
hides and skin, according to industrial operators.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that at least 60 percent of the industry will
close down by July unless timely actions are taken to check
smuggling of local hides and skin into neighboring India.
</P>
<P>
The tanning industry usually collects 40 percent of its total
supply during the Muslim Eid days, when animals are ritually
slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
But this year the industry has virtually failed to procure its
share from the market mainly due to fund shortage. And absence of
tanners from the market has resulted in a drastic fall in prices
of hides and skin.
</P>
<P>
Taking this opportunity, according to industry sources, traders
from India have been active in smuggling out local hides and skin
worth about 2 billion taka (about 50 million U.S. dollars) from
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the trend is checked, the industry will face a serious
setback," said Ali Hossain, secretary general of Bangladesh Hide
and Skin Merchants Association.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
