<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Samsonov Shows Maturity Beyond His Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 23 (Xinhua) -- As one of the world
best players, Vladimir Samsonov has demonstrated that the
innocent, boyish look is a mere guise for a crafty, lynx-like
animal constantly on the prowl for preys.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old star from Belarus, ranked fourth in the world,
is a force to reckon with in the 44th World Table Tennis
Championships which begins here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"His childish look is very deceptive," said Xu Yinsheng, chief
of the Chinese Table Tennis Association. "He is very fast on feet
and plays a consistent game without obvious loopholes."
</P>
<P>
Xu, who also heads the International Table Tennis Federation,
tipped Samsonov as a title-hopeful in the men's singles event
which kicks off on April 30.
</P>
<P>
Standing 1.88 meters, the lanky Belarussian is willing to rally
until his rival leaves an opening. Once he gets chance, his
lethal forehands rarely fail him.
</P>
<P>
"I think his forehand is the most heaviest in the world,"
commented German world No. 9 Jorg Rosskopf, who will partner
Samsonov to bid for the men's doubles title here.
</P>
<P>
The high-toss serve, invented by Chinese in 1960s, has become
one of the assets for Samsonov. His rivals often misjudge amount
of spin he put on serves, giving him a chance to make a kill.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov is also good at minute and fine maneuvers on the
table, rare for a player of such height.
</P>
<P>
"European players are known for strong loop drives away from
table but not so good at playing short ball. Samsonov is an
exception," said Chinese coach Yin Xiao.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese men's team has put Samsonov and Sweden's world
No. 2 Jan-Ove Waldner as their top threats. "Samsonov and Waldner
are the best all-around players in Europe," said Chinese head
coach Cai Zhenhua.
</P>
<P>
To surprise of Chinese fans, the nation's secret weapon Ding
Song, who had caught top European players nonplused by his
chop-and-attack style in the 1995 world championships, is never a
secret to Samsonov.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov showed composure beyond his years in the World Cup
last October, outlasting Ding in five sets in their first meeting.
</P>
<P>
In the Qatar Open in February, revengeful Ding once again fell
under the consistent topspin play by Samsonov.
</P>
<P>
Ding vows to take a revenge in the Manchester Worlds, but the
Chinese coach said Ding's chance to beat Samsonov was slim. "I
don't count on him," Cai said.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov caught limelight at 16 as he upset Swedish star Peter
Karlsson in the Gothenburg championships in 1993 and narrowly lost
a quarter-final berth to Rosskopf after a five-set marathon in the
1995 event.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov should have come into the medal contention in the
Olympic Games last summer if there weren't a 20-minute delay
during his game against Wang Tao.
</P>
<P>
With Samsonov leading 2-0, an unusual electricity blackout in
the court gave a breather to the jaded Wang, who snatched three
sets in a row to shut his rival out of the last four.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov reached his peak in the European Masters Cup one month
after the Olympics, beating five world elite players to win his
first major title.
</P>
<P>
Waldner rated Samsonov and Rosskopf as odds-on favorites for
the men's doubles event. "They have better teamwork than any
other combinations and have a very good chance to be champions in
Manchester," he said.
</P>
<P>
The pair of different nationalities had beaten world champions
Wang Tao and Lu Lin and Olympic doubles gold medalists Liu
Guoliang and Kong Linghui in the Pro-Tour Grand Prix Finals last
December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
