<HEADLINE> Japanese FM Leaves For Peru to Relay Thanks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister Yukihiko
Ikeda left Tokyo for Lima today to convey Japan's gratitude to the
Peruvian government over ending the four-month-long hostage crisis
at the Japanese ambassador's residence.
</P>
<P>
"I will express gratitude to President Alberto Fujimori and the
Peruvian government, which realized the release of the hostages,"
Ikeda told a press conference before departing for Lima.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said he will also express condolences to
relatives of those who died during the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian security forces stormed the Japanese ambassador's
residence in Lima Tuesday afternoon on the 127th day of the siege,
rescuing 71 of the 72 hostages and killing all of the 14
hostage-takers from the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA).
</P>
<P>
All of the 24 Japanese hostages, including Ambassador Morihisa
Aoki, were rescued alive.
</P>
<P>
Relatives of some of the released Japanese hostages and
investigators from Japan's National Police Agency will also be on
board the chartered plane that will take Ikeda to Peru. 
</P>
