<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Become Self-Sufficient in Food: Sharif </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said today that his country would become self-sufficient in
food grains in the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
The government has worked out a plan to provide incentives to
grains growers to meet the desired objectives, Sharif said while
handing over land to landless peasants at a ceremony held at a
village near Larkana, northern city of Sindh Province.
</P>
<P>
He noted that at present the country is spending about 90
billion rupees (over 2 billion U.S. dollars) yearly on the import
of food grains and other food items.
</P>
<P>
But with an increase in the wheat support price, the growers
will take to wheat cultivation, thus leading the country to
self-sufficiency, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government's plan does not comprise only granting land to
farmers, but it also envisages provision of seeds, fertilizer,
tractors and other inputs so that they may be able to develop and
cultivate their lands, Sharif said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
