<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Needs New Paddy Fields: Soeharto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
today called on the people to open new paddy fields to meet the
increasing demand of rice in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We will face difficulty in maintaining our self-sufficiency in
rice and import them again if we do not open new rice fields," the
president said when inaugurating the country's longest bridge, the
1,082-meter-long Barito bridge in Beringin village, in south
Kalimantan province, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, who observed a one-million hectare peatland project
which is converting into a rice field in central Kalimantan,
before inaugurating the bridge, stressed there is urgency in
opening new rice fields in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said many rice fields have been converted into industrial
zones, resettlement areas, roads and for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 200 million, Indonesia achieved
self-sufficient in rice in 1984. However, the country is currently
under threat as rice-fields are being eaten away by industrial
expansion and disturbed by unfriendly weather.
</P>
<P>
According to data published by the Ministry of Agriculture,
unhulled rice production reached 50.032 million tons in 1996, only
up 0.58 percent compared to the 49.744 million tons in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
