<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Champ Kong Faces Real Test in Table Tennis Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China's world No. 1
Kong Linghui, the reigning world men's singles champion and the
1995 World Cup winner, will find himself in the unusual role of
underdog in the 44th World Table Tennis Championships which begins
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cai Zhenhua, head coach of the Chinese men's squad, declined to
speculate on Kong's singles campaign, saying the top 20 players in the
world all stood a chance to win the conveted singles title.
</P>
<P>
"I won't be surprised if anyone in the world top 20 rankings
wins the singles event," Cai said.
</P>
<P>
"I won't be surprised either if anyone among the first echelon
is defeated by the rest of the world top 100 players," he added.
</P>
<P>
The men's singles game has been so closely contested that no
one has succeeded in defending his title since Chinese Jiang
Jialiang won the championship in 1985 and 1987.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's Jan-Ove Waldner lifted the singles title in 1989 and
conceded it to teammate Jorgen Persson in 1991. Frenchman
Jean-Philippe Gatien took the 1993 event and fell under a
giant-killing spree by Kong in the 1995 Worlds.
</P>
<P>
"It is much more difficult to win back-to-back in the men's
singles event since so many good players are out there," Cai said.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese men's players now have no advantage over the rest of
the world," the coach added.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old Kong, a player willing to rally until his
opponent makes errors or leaves an opening, faces a herculean job
to defend the singles title after a lackluster year dotted with
defeats to South Koreans and Europeans.
</P>
<P>
Kong has been struggling to find former self since a form
reversal caused a defeat to South Korean Kim Taek Soo in the
Atlanta Olympic Games last summer.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese continued his poor form in the World Cup last
September, finishing third in the group after losses to Waldner
and Brazilian Koyama Yugo.
</P>
<P>
Kong then twice lost his team match to the 98th-ranked South
Korean Ou Sang Eun in the Asian championships last December and
Qatar Open in February.
</P>
<P>
South Koreans, known for tenacious spirits and blistering
forehand attacks, are arch rivals for the Chinese, Cai said.
</P>
<P>
Even though Kong avenged his Olympic loss to Kim in the singles
semi-finals at the Asian championships, beating the world best
penholding looper 3-1, pundits hold that the Chinese only has a
fifty-fifty chance against the South Korean if they meet again.
</P>
<P>
The other player able to end Kong's singles run in the
Manchester Worlds is Waldner, the 1992 Olympic champion famed for
his wickedly deceptive serves and ferocious follow-up attacks.
</P>
<P>
Kong has met the Swede four times and lost all encounters.
</P>
<P>
The last time Kong faced the 31-year-old Swede across the net
was the Qatar Open, where the Chinese lost his singles semi-final
3-1.
</P>
<P>
"I have played against Waldner once every year since 1994,"
said Kong. "Even though I lost all four meetings, I think I have
been closing the gap with him."
</P>
<P>
"I have confidence to beat Waldner if I meet him in
Manchester," Kong added.
</P>
<P>
Waldner, who has won the European Top 12 title for seven times,
tipped reigning Olympic and World Cup champion Liu Guoliang
instead as a favorite Chinese for the men's singles title.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese are able to collect four gold medals in this
championships and Liu Guoliang will very likely become the singles
champion, " said Waldner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
