<HEADLINE> ASEAN Should Stick to Accepting Myanmar: Thai PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh said here today that despite the United States'
Unilateral economic sanctions against Myanmar, ASEAN should stick
to its decision on accepting Myanmar as a member.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said at the Government House that the decision of
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) is one made by
ASEAN, not by others, stressing that ASEAN should pursue its 1995
decision on inclusion of Myanmar in ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright announced on
Tuesday a ban on new investment by Americans in Myanmar because of
human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the ban, Chavalit said that his government has not
received any request from the U.S. government to join the ban.
</P>
<P>
Under an ASEAN resolution, ASEAN is expected to take in
Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar as ASEAN's new members in July this
year.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit plans to make a visit to Myanmar on May 3-4.  
</P>
</TEXT>
