<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Up After Inflation Rates Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar rose today
after inflation numbers released which showed that the March
consumer price index falling to its lowest level in four years.
</P>
<P>
But the result was mildly positive because it was at the higher
end of market expectations, Bankers Trust foreign exchange dealer
Matt Gilmour said.
</P>
<P>
Traders pointed out that a string of major economic data would
be released in the U.S. next week which could prompt sell-offs on
fixed interest markets.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollars closed at 77.82 US cents from 77.57 at
Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar rose, it closed at
98.03 yen from 97.61 yen against the Japanese yen and at 1.3323
marks from 1.3211 marks against the German mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
