<HEADLINE> First Two Sheep Cloned From Embryo Cells Pregnant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The first two sheep cloned from
laboratory-grown embryo cells are to become mothers, showing that
the cloning does no harm the self-reproduction of cloned animals,
the Daily Telegraph reported today.
</P>
<P>
The mother-to-be twins, named Megan and Morag, were cloned from
cells from the early embryo of a Welsh mountain sheep by
researchers at the Roslin Institute two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The work on Megan and Morag was an important precursor to the
cloning of a Finn Dorset lamb called Dolly, when Ian Wilmut and
his team at the same institute used cells from an adult.
</P>
<P>
The Edinburgh-based institute said on Tuesday that Morag and
Megan were both pregnant, quelling fears that the sheep, who share
a pen with Dolly, might not be able to conceive as a result of
being cloned.
</P>
<P>
"This is a further demonstration of their normality," as both
ewes have conceived by normal means, said Harry Griffin, assistant
director of the institute.
</P>
<P>
Morag is due to give birth next month while Megan's lamb is
expected in July.
</P>
<P>
Concern over the damage the cloning might bring to the sheep
rests on the difficulty of the technique.
</P>
<P>
Only six in every 10 attempts made in the Megan/Morag
experiments worked. After much effort, five clones were produced,
but three sisters died -- two within minutes of birth and the
third within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Post-mortem examinations revealed abnormalities in their
kidneys and cardiovascular system. The lambs tended to be large
for their breed and one had to be delivered by Caesarean section.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
