<HEADLINE> Stock Market Plunge Only Temporary, Says Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Ramos today
assured the people that the Tuesday's downward plunge of the
Manila stock market "is just a temporary aberration".
</P>
<P>
In his weekly press conference, Ramos said that the stock
market has already begun to recover this morning with the index
going up 48 points.
</P>
<P>
The country's stock market experienced the biggest drop in five
months Tuesday as the stock index fell by 84.53 points, or 2.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
Some feared that the plunge indicated the country's real estate
companies were facing financial problems similar to those in
Thailand, where the financial system has been crippled by loan
defaults to the real estate industry.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the country is economically stable because the
macro-economic fundamentals have been imbedded in the law and
their transparency and continuity have been guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
The president pointed to the success in the auction of two
billion pesos (76 million US dollar) worth of 20-year fixed rate
treasury bonds with an interest of 14.375 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the auction was an "overwhelming success" because of
the lower than expected quadruple rate and people's confidence to
invest in a longer term "and wait for the results to come in
little by little in due time over a period of 20 years."  
</P>
</TEXT>
