<HEADLINE> PATA Annual Conference Ends in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A leading official of the Pacific
Asia Travel Association (PATA) has expressed appreciation and high
praise for China's hard work to make a success of the 46th PATA
Annual Conference, which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
PATA President and CEO Lakshman Ratnapala described China's
organization of the annual conference and two related events,
the '97 Chapters World Congress in Shanghai and the '97 PATA
Travel Mart in Beijing, as "excellent."
</P>
<P>
He added that the events have promoted understanding and
communication among China's travel industry and its counterparts
from elsewhere in the world, and created more business
opportunities for tourism companies attending the events.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Drysdale, the outgoing 1996/97 PATA Chairman, also
praised the professionalism of the Chinese host committee and its
commitment to making the conference a success.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,500 delegates from 51 countries attended the annual
conference of one of the world's most influential tourist
organizations.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day event, the delegates shared their views on
marketing techniques, the role of modern telecommunications
technology and the media in market development, and on sustainable
development with its focus on environmental conservation.
</P>
<P>
Jon Hutchison, newly elected PATA 1997/98 Chairman, stressed
the association's responsibility in environmental protection, and
promoting the varied cultures of different nations.
</P>
<P>
An annual report issued by PATA expressed a highly optimistic
view of the prospect of tourism in the Asia-Pacific region, saying
with the center of the global economy shifting to the region, its
travel industry has become fastest-growing in the world.
</P>
<P>
China places great importance on the PATA conference, which was
the biggest and highest-level international meeting on tourism
ever held in China. Premier Li Peng attended the opening ceremony
on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
