<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Company Applies to Invest in DPRK: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean land company has
applied to develop an industrial estate in the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), a government official said today.
</P>
<P>
The Korea Land Corporation's industrial estate will be in the
DPRK's Rajin-sonbong Free Economic and Trade Zone, said Cho
Hun-shik, director-general of the National Unification Ministry's
Inter-Korean Interchange and Cooperation Bureau.
</P>
<P>
He also said the company signed a letter of intent with DPRK
officials in Beijing on April 20 and submitted an application for
a license to the ministry the next day.
</P>
<P>
The company plans to develop a 6.6 million square meter
industrial estate in the economic zone with an investment of 500
million to 600 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the first stage of the project, it will invest some 100
million dollars to develop an area of 1.3 million square meters.
</P>
<P>
The estate, which will include factories, transportation and
support facilities, and residence, is to accommodate small- and
medium-sized South Korean and foreign firms.
</P>
<P>
The official said the government will decide on the application
after making a cautious study of the document. 
</P>
</TEXT>
