<HEADLINE> Singapore Firm in Joint Venture to Invest in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Technologies
Industrial Corporation (STIC), a government-linked firm, went into
partnership with Asian movie giant Golden Harvest in a joint
venture to invest in cinemas in China, local media reported here
today.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, in a deal sealed on Tuesday, the
joint-venture company, Golden-STIC, will invest up to two million
US dollars in a six-screen multiplex cinema in Shanghai. Located
near the heart of Shanghai, the cinema is one of the first in
China with foreign equity participation.
</P>
<P>
The 1,300-seat Shanghai multiplex will be in the Hai Xing
Complex, a commercial, retail and residential development. It will
open in August with four screens and the remaining two screens
will be ready by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
If successful, the venture will be expanded to more sites in
Shanghai and other major cities across China, the STIC was quoted
as saying in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Golden-STIC is a 50-50 joint venture between STIC's wholly
owned subsidiary, STIC Investments, and Golden Harvest's Singapore
subsidiary, Golden Harvest Multiplex.
</P>
<P>
Golden Harvest chairman Raymond Chow, who is also chairman of
the joint-venture company, said, "We are very excited about the
prospects of the movie industry in China. Besides investing in
movie production, we are keen to invest in improving the quality
of cinemas in China."
</P>
<P>
The STIC president and chief executive Tay Siew Choon said the
investment showed STIC's strategy to broaden its leisure and
lifestyle business through investments in new areas and to reduce
its dependence on the Singapore market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
