<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Gov't, Opposition Fail to Reach Tax Reform Compromise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The German government and the main
opposition party in Bonn said today that they have failed to
strike a compromise on a government plan to overhaul the country
taxation system.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Oskar Lafontaine, leader of the main
opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) met for only one hour
Wednesday in Bonn before announcing the failure of negotiations
which began in February.
</P>
<P>
Both sides blamed the failure of the talks on the other. The
government said in a written statement that the SPD was standing
in the way of a structural reform of the taxation system which was
necessary for economic growth and job creation.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine said Kohl's ruling coalition had deliberately
destroyed the negotiations. The SPD had been ready for tax reforms
even in 1997 and 1998, instead of the government's plan for 1999,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The tax reform plan, proposed by Finance Minister Theo Waigel,
is believed to be the country's biggest tax-revision package since
1949. Aiming at bolstering business confidence, investment and
hiring, it has become the government's top domestic policy
priority and its main recipe to curb record high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
But the realization of the major initiative depends on the
approval of the SPD, which controls a majority in the Bundesrat,
the upper house of the German parliament.
</P>
<P>
A failure of the negotiations means that the tax plan will
begin wending its way through parliamentary committees without
prior approval from the SPD, raising fear that politicians and
interest groups will water down the plan and blunt its edge to
increase investment and hiring.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed tax reform package, the government wants,
among other things, to cut income taxes to 15 percent for low-wage
earners and 39 percent for people with high incomes instead of the
current marginal rates ranging from 25.9 percent to 53
percent. Business revenue tax would also be axed from 47 percent
to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
Government says the package will yield 30 billion marks (17.6
billion U.S. dollars) in net annual tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
The SPD, however, has spoken in favor of keeping the top income
rate at 53 percent or trimming it only modestly, a strategy meant
to keep the tax burden on those best suited to pay.
</P>
<P>
It also wants to boost spending of low-income families by
reducing non-wage labour costs. To the offset the financial
shortfall, it proposed to raise gasoline taxes.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the SPD and the government have held three rounds of
tax negotiations since February 26, but all failed to make
headway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Scientists Achieves Progress in New Gene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot scientists have for the
first time made progress in gene therapy by mapping the gene that
causes a hereditary muscular disease to one of the human body's 23
chromosomes, thus paving the way for the eventual treatment of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency (CNA) today, scientists from
the Cyprus Institute of Neurology and Genetics reported to
colleagues at the annual meeting of the American Academy of
Neurology in Boston last week that they have mapped the gene
of the familial form of myasthenia to chromosome 17p.
</P>
<P>
Myasthenia is characterized by the progressive weakness and
exhaustibility of voluntary muscles, such as those of the arms
and legs.
</P>
<P>
Geneticist Kyproulla Christodoulou, one of the four research
group member, was quoted as saying that "this is the first step
to help in gene therapy."
</P>
<P>
"Now we can find out what this gene does and why it
causes the disease, and from there we can suggest ways to
treat it," Christodoulou added.
</P>
<P>
CNA said that the Cypriot presentation at the annual
meeting of the American Academy of Neurology was one of the
five "late breaking news" among 1,200 scientific presentations.
</P>
<P>
The results of the Cypriot scientists' research are published
in the April issue of the international scientific journal
"Human Molecular Genetics".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
