<HEADLINE> Registration for Presidential Race to Start in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government announced
today that presidential nominees will start registration for the
7th presidential elections, scheduled for a period from April 24
to 28.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Tehran Radio reported that the announcement was
made by Interior Minister Ali Mohammad Besharati at the
premises of the ministry in downtown Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The minister set the deadline for the registration which
will last for five days from 7 a.m. Thursday to 4 p.m.
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry would send a list of the candidates to
the Guardian Council the following day. The council will
scrutinize them in view of their qualification.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Interior Minister Gholamhussain Bolandian said that the
top priority of his ministry was to protect the legal rights
and safeguard the votes cast by the people in the forthcoming
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
So far, a dozen of dignities, including three ruling clergymen,
have declared themselves as nominees for the 7th presidential
elections, which are scheduled for May 23.
</P>
<P>
They include Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri, former
minister of culture and Islamic guidance Mohammad Khatami,
former minister of information Mohammad Mohammadi Reyshahri and
deputy head of the judiciary Seyed Reza Zavarei.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the 54-year-old parliament speaker
is the front-runner who has a big chance of winning the
presidential race though he lacks the competence and qualifications
for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the main factor of his victory is the
support by Iran's Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei and the rightist
camp called the Association of Combatant Clergymen.
</P>
<P>
However, some political analysts said that the mild and
open personality of Mohammad Khatami is attracting more and more
support from the public, especially the educated people.
</P>
<P>
There will be a fierce battle between the two clergymen.
</P>
<P>
The next president will assume office in August.
</P>
<P>
Since Iran's Constitution bars present President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani from running for a third consecutive term, so the
64-year-old president has to step down.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that Rafsanjani will still remain as No. 2
man only after Iran's Supreme Leader
Khamenei. 
</P>
</TEXT>
