<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Banking System on Verge of Collapse: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Governor of Bangladesh Bank Lutfor
Rahman Sarker has said that the country's banking system is on the
verge of collapse because of default loans.
</P>
<P>
"The country's legal framework for realizing loans is very
weak, as a result, realization of bank loans has become a
complicated issue," the central bank governor was quoted by the
English-language Independent today.
</P>
<P>
The governor said the banking sector is burdened with
outstanding loans to the tune of 130 billion taka (about 3.25
billion U.S. dollars), of which "50 billion taka (about 1.25
billion dollars) remains with 137 persons who can pay back but are
not doing so."
</P>
<P>
Pleading for framing a strong legal framework, the governor
said it was needed for building up a strong banking system to
infuse dynamism in the economy.
</P>
<P>
A few months ago, the central bank urged all commercial banks
to speed up the realization of default loans. However, the move
failed to create much response.
</P>
<P>
Lutfor Rahman Sarker expressed the need for application of
criminal laws for recovering the loans as civil cases proved
ineffective against the defaulters.
</P>
<P>
New criminal law should be formulated to deal with the
defaulters, he said, urging the concerned authorities to take
action against the defaulters to save the country's banking
sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
