<HEADLINE> American Olympic Champion to Run in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Olympic champion Michael Johnson
of the United States will take part at an IAAF meet in Sheffield
this summer, the British Athletic Federation (BAF) said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
BAF announced that Johnson, who won gold medals in the 200
meters and 400 meters at the Atlanta Olympics, will compete in the
400 at the Securicor Games in Sheffield on June 29.
</P>
<P>
It will be Johnson's first appearance in Britain in more than
three years. He last ran at an indoor meet in Birmingham in
1994. He had previously raced in Sheffield in 1991 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Johnson was denied a place in the 400m at a meet in
London. Organizers said they didn't want Johnson to demoralize
his British rivals just before the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
Johnson threatened never to run in Britain again, but
Wednesday's announcement indicated he has come to terms with the
BAF. No mention was made of how much he will receive for running
in Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
Johnson began his 1997 outdoor season last Saturday in Waco,
Texas, winning the 400m in 43.75 seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
