<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pakistan's Budget Deficit to Rise As </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Public debt crisis, the
long-running problem facing Pakistan's economy, is worsening as
the federal government continues its excessive borrowings from the
banking system for the purpose of budgetary support.
</P>
<P>
With only three months left before the end of the current
fiscal year, the prospects of reducing the budget deficit to a
sustainable level by intensifying efforts for tax collection and
cutting down expenditure appears to be dim.
</P>
<P>
Figures available here show that by the end of March, the
federal government had borrowed 74.3 billion rupees (about 1.9
billion US dollars) from the banking system. This exceeds the
actual allocation of 44 billion rupees (11 billion dollars) fixed
for the whole financial year.
</P>
<P>
It is for certain that the budget deficit is to be further
widened as mandatory limits for the government's bank borrowing
had exceeded by more than 59 percent while three months of the
current fiscal year are still left.
</P>
<P>
Economists here believe that during the remaining three month
of 1996-97 fiscal year, the government's borrowings from the banks
may further rise.
</P>
<P>
During the corresponding period of the last fiscal year, the
bank borrowings by the Federal government were only 33.3 billion
rupees (830 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the government's borrowings far in
excess of the given limit in the first three quarters of the
current fiscal year are primarily due to the political crisis that
kept this nation in its grip for almost eight months.
</P>
<P>
The eight-month period covers three administrations -- the
government led by the Pakistan People's Party, the caretakers and
the government of the Pakistan Muslim League (N) -- none of which
could have enough time to reorder and enforce its financial
policies and collect taxes in pursuit of those policies.
</P>
<P>
The latest official figures show that by the end of March, tax
revenues have registered a huge shortfall of 42 billion rupees
(one billion dollars) against the original target of 222 billion
rupees (55 billion dollars) and of 24 billion rupees (571.4
million dollars) against the reduced target of 204 billion rupees
(51 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, expenditure had also exceeded budgetary allocations.
Therefore, it will be an extremely difficult job for the
government to bring the budget deficit appreciably down by
increasing tax revenue and reducing expenditure before the end of
the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Pakistan Muslim League led by Nawaz
Sharif is now engaged in formulating various packages on the
priority in a bid to spur up industrial production and bring about
buoyancy in economic activity on a wide front.
</P>
<P>
The recent economic revival policy concentrating mainly on tax
reform will certainly help increase savings, investment and
production and, consequently, higher collection of revenue.
However, the new economic policy needs a time-lag to succeed.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's overall economic situation this year is tough. As
the shortage of wheat is persisting, scarcity of other agri
products like sugar and cooking oil is also being predicted for
the coming months.
</P>
<P>
All the indications show that the budget deficit this year will
increase, and there is less likelihood of an escape for the
government from bank borrowings in the remaining three months of
the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the problem of budget deficit is
crucial to successful implementation of monetary and banking
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the caretaker government made certain vital
decisions about financial reforms which include enhancement of the
autonomy and independent functioning of the State Bank of Pakistan
(SBP).
</P>
<P>
The relatively easier access of the government to bank
borrowings does not seem to have changed despite the amendments
recently made in State Bank Act through an ordinance that SBP
besides other matters, has been authorized to exercise a check on
the government's bank borrowings.
</P>
<P>
It appears that SBP has not yet started to use its powers for
discouraging the government from exceeding its limits in respect
of borrowings from the banking system.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the real implementation of financial
reforms will help do away with the political influences on the
banking system. The government should gradually reduce its
dependence on bank borrowings by making efforts to raise its
resources through appropriate taxation measures.
</P>
<P>
However, the rise in government's bank borrowings clearly
indicates that tax collections have not picked up momentum, and a
sizable amount of budget deficit is to continue which will greatly
affect the implementation of the government's all macro economic
reforms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
