<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Gives Speech at Russian Duma (Part I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin, on
a five-day state visit to Russia, today delivered a speech at the
Russian State Duma (the lower house of parliament), entitled
"Working Together for the Establishment of a Just and Equitable
New International Order." The full text of the speech reads as
follows:

Respected Chairman Seleznev,
Friends,
Ladies and Gentlemen,
</P>
<P>
One year after the visit to China by President Yeltsin, I am in
Russia again to pay yet another state visit to our great
neighbor. It is an exceptional honor and pleasure for me to meet
here today with the respected deputies to the State Duma of the
Russian Federation. I would like to take this opportunity to
convey to you and the Russian people the cordial greetings and
best wishes of the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
This morning, in a cordial and sincere atmosphere, President
Yeltsin and I held our fourth summit meeting and signed the Joint
Statement. And very soon the heads of state of China, Russia,
Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan will sign the Agreement on
Mutual Reduction of Military Forces in the Border Areas. The
important achievements of this visit go far beyond the context of
bilateral relations and will greatly enhance peace and stability
in the region and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
Mankind is about to conclude yet another century. Looking
back, we see the century saturated with untold human sufferings as
a result of wars and threats of wars. The two world wars in the
first half of the century have brought catastrophic agonies to the
world's people, including the Chinese and Russians. The second
half of the century saw the Cold War that lasted over forty years
accompanied by incessant regional conflicts which gravely impeded
the advancement of global peace and development.
</P>
<P>
Past tragedies must not be allowed to repeat. Having
sacrificed heavily for winning and safeguarding world peace, we
appreciate all the more deeply the value of peace. At this turn
of the century, how to advance the noble cause of peace and
development in the 21st century has become the key question that
statesmen and people around the world must seriously study and
resolve.
</P>
<P>
The world is moving towards multipolarization, a hallmark of
the present-day international situation. At both global and
regional levels, in both political and economic arenas, the trend
of multipolarization is picking up speed. The time when a few big
powers or power blocs could monopolize world affairs and dictate
the fate of others has gone for good. The relations between and
among big powers are in constant shifts and a multitude of power
centers is now taking shape. With increased overall strength and
elevated status, the developing countries have become an important
force on the international scene to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
Regional organizations of various types are increasingly
active, displaying robust dynamism. Though it will still take a
long process for a multipolar world to take place, the trend has
already become an irresistible historical tide which takes on a
crucial significance for the promotion of peace, stability and
development in the world.
</P>
<P>
With the end of the Cold War, global forces for peace have
gained strength. Yes to mutual respect, equality and mutual
benefit and no to hegemonism and power politics. Yes to dialogue
and cooperation and no to confrontation and conflict. This has
become the consensus of more and more countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
