<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Gives Speech at Russian Duma (Part II) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As early as in the 1980s, Comrade Deng Xiaoping, after a
scientific analysis of the major and profound changes in the
world, put forth the proposition for the establishment of a just
and equitable new international political and economic order.
This initiative of great vision and far-reaching significance has
since been enthusiastically embraced by the international
community. We in China stand ready to join statesmen of various
countries in making concerted efforts to promote the establishment
of this new international order.
</P>
<P>
This new international order is based on the Five Principles of
Peaceful Coexistence. Facts have amply proved that these
principles are consistent with the purposes of the United Nations
Charter, perfectly workable in practice, and reflect the essential
characteristics of a new type of international relations. They
have already become universally recognized norms in international
community.
</P>
<P>
Under the new international order, each country has the right
to choose independently its own development path in light of its
national conditions and no other country has the right to
interfere in. The world is a diverse and colorful place, where
countries differ form each other in terms of historical
background, social system, development level, cultural tradition
and values. These differences, instead of posing barriers to the
development of normal state-to-state relations, should serve as
driving forces behind closer exchanges and cooperation of
countries and greater common development and progress. Imposing
one's own social system and ideology on other countries in
international relations is absolutely unacceptable, and trying to
do so will go nowhere. Only by respecting the independent choices
of various peoples, seeking common ground while setting aside
differences and refraining from interference in each other's
internal affairs can countries live with each other in harmony and
can our world enjoy genuine peace and tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
Under this new international order, all countries, big or
small, strong or weak, rich or poor, are treated as equal members
of the international community and no country should be allowed to
seek hegemony or go in for power politics. Major countries should
shoulder greater responsibility and obligation in maintaining
world peace and stability, reducing armament, promoting
development of all countries and protecting human environment.
Yet this is by no means to suggest that they may dominate the
world or enjoy a privilege to monopolize international affairs.
Matters that fall within the jurisdiction of a country's
sovereignty should be handled by that country, and the affairs of
the world should be handled by all the countries through
consultations on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
Under this new international order, countries are called upon
to use peaceful means to settle their differences or disputes,
instead of resorting to the use or threat of force. They should
increase mutual understanding and trust through dialogues and
consultations and gradually iron out their differences and
problems by way of multilateral or bilateral coordination and
cooperation. Cold War mentality and all other practices
detrimental to world peace and development must be resolutely
discarded. The agreement to be signed by our five countries on
the reduction of military forces gives full expression to a new
security concept that is completely different from the Cold War
mentality. It will offer a useful revelation and open up a new way
for countries to enhance friendship and trust and to maintain
regional and world peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Gives Speech at Russian Duma (Part III) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Under this new international order, countries are urged to
solidify and expand their economic, scientific, technological and
cultural exchanges and cooperation on the basis of equality and
mutual benefit and to promote common development and prosperity.
Unequal and discriminatory policies and practices in economic and
trade relations must be rejected, still less should arbitrary use
of so-called economic sanctions against other countries be
allowed. The world economy is an interrelated and interdependent
whole. The developing countries need the capital and technology
of the developed countries and the developed countries need the
raw materials and market of the developing countries. The
developed countries should respect the interests and needs of the
developing countries and increase their economic input and
technical aid to the latter. If the North-South relations are not
improved and their gap remains wide, it will hurt poor countries
and serves no interest of rich countries either. What is more, it
brings no assurances for world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Having been subjected to aggression and humiliation by foreign
powers for more than a century in its modern history, China
understands full well how hard-won its peace and independence
are. The Chinese people love and cherish peace. Our ongoing
reform, opening up and modernization drive require a peaceful
international environment. We have always pursued an independent
foreign policy of peace and dedicated ourselves to maintaining
world peace and stability and promoting the common development of
all countries. The Chinese Government has stated on many
occasions that China will not participate in arms race, join any
military bloc, or engage in military expansion, nor will it ever
seek hegemony. China has made a unilateral commitment on
unconditional non-first use of nuclear weapons and unconditional
non-use or threat of use of nuclear weapons against non-nuclear
states. China stands for complete prohibition and thorough
destruction of nuclear weapons and supports the establishment of
nuclear-free zones in Latin America, Asia-Pacific, Africa and
other regions. China has provided Ukraine and Kazakhstan with
nuclear security assurances respectively. China and Russia have
announced the mutual detargeting of their nuclear warheads and
mutual non-first use of nuclear weapons against each other.
China, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan have reached
an agreement on the reduction of military forces in the areas
along their border of more than 7,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The practice of China's foreign policy fully demonstrates that
China is a positive factor and a strong force in the maintenance
of regional and world peace. China's development contributes to
global stability, and a prosperous China means a stronger force
for peace. History has proved repeatedly that whether a nation
poses a threat to world peace is not determined by its power but
by the nature of its domestic and foreign policies. China's
domestic policy is one of wholehearted commitment to socialist
modernization and its foreign policy of independence and peace.
We will not change the fundamental principles underlying these
policies. We will, as always, make unremitting efforts to
safeguard peace in the region and in the world at large.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
