<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Coffee Export Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- India's coffee exports declined
by 6.5 percent in terms of volume and 15 percent in value during
1996-97, the Press Trust of India quoted Coffee Board Chairman
Philippse Mathai as saying here today.
</P>
<P>
The decline was in sharp contrast to the splendid performance
during 1995-96 when coffee exports went up by 23 percent from a
year earlier, Mathai said.
</P>
<P>
As per provisional figures, India exported 160,000 tons of
coffee in 1996-97, fetching 380 million U.S. dollars. In 1995-96,
however, coffee exports hit a record of 171,000 tons, earning 450
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
One major reason for the drop in coffee exports was good
domestic prices, which were 50 percent higher than those on the
world market, he said.
</P>
<P>
India is likely to produce a record 233,000 tons of coffee
during the 1997-98 crop year, Mathai added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
