<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flying Pilgrims Is Iraq's Legitimate Right, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 23 (Xinhua) -- It is Iraq's legitimate right to
fly its pilgrims to Mecca, Saudi Arabia, for hajj home and Iraq
has not violated any U.N. resolution, an Iraqi English newspaper
said today.
</P>
<P>
Naji al-Hadithi, editor-in-chief of the Baghdad Observer, said
in an editorial that the measures taken by the Iraqi government to
fly returning Iraqi pilgrims from Iraqi-Saudi borders to their
home towns "constituted a legitimate exercise of (Iraq's)
sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that this move violated no U.N. resolutions but
"was in conformity with international laws and the U.N. charter
as well as with Iraq's full sovereign rights of acting within
its own border and in its own space."
</P>
<P>
The editorial also described a no-fly zone in southern Iraq
as "clear defiance of international law and the U.N. charter
which unequivocally respect the sovereignty of all nations."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government sent eight military helicopters Monday and
Tuesday to its border town of Ar'ar to pick up about 100 elderly
and sick Iraqi pilgrims, who went to Mecca for hajj on board an
Iraqi passenger plane on April 9. That was the first international
flight by Iraq after the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters crossed the no-fly zone imposed in southern
Iraq by the U.S., Britain and France after the Gulf War, and
landed safely at the Iraqi-Saudi border area, about 350
kilometers southwest of Baghdad, the capital of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government expressed deep concern and anger over the
matter and said Iraq should have asked for U.N. permission to cross
the no-fly zone in advance.
</P>
<P>
Washington insisted that the flight violated U.N. resolutions
661 and 670 adopted after Iraq's August 1990 invasion of Kuwait,
which declared an airborne blockade on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
