<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The performance of Thailand's
banking sector in the first quarter this year was not as
satisfactory as expected, as most commercial banks saw a slowdown
compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Stock Exchange of Thailand, almost all local
commercial banks reported a low growth and some saw less net
profits than a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Thai Farmers Bank, one of the leading commercial banks in the
country, reported a net profit of 2.65 billion baht (106 million
U.S. dollars) in the first quarter of this year, down 11.9 percent
from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Thai Military Bank and Krung Thai Bank also saw a 23-percent
and a 23.7-percent decrease in net profit respectively in the
period.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Bank, another leading commercial bank in Thailand,
registered a net profit of 5.024 billion baht (201 million
dollars) during the period, up only 0.3 percent, but Siam
Commercial Bank fared much better with a net profit of 2.227
billion baht (89.1 million dollars), up 9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thai commercial banks also saw a slowdown in their lending. The
total lending by local commercial banks was posted at 12.48
trillion baht (about 499.16 billion dollars) in the first three
months of this year, an average growth of only 0.73 percent per
month compared with the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the banks saw a low savings growth, with the
total savings they received in the period amounting to 11 trillion
baht (440 billion dollars), an average increase of only 1.18
percent per month compared with the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts blamed the central bank's reserves regulations
and the sluggish economy for the dismal performance of local
commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand, the country's central bank, currently
requires commercial banks to set aside a 15-percent reserve to
cover substandard assets and an 8-percent reserve to cover regular
loans.
</P>
<P>
Some commercial banks complained that they are receiving less
earnings as they are forced to inject more funds into reserves.
</P>
<P>
However, some bankers pointed out that the central bank's
regulations on reserves would make financial institutions stronger
in the long run and prevent them from crises in the future.
</P>
<P>
Currently, some banks are taking measures consolidate their
positions, hoping that their performance will improve in the rest
of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
