<HEADLINE> U.S. Sanction Not to Affect Myanmar Joining ASEAN: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said today that the decision of the United States
to impose economic sanctions on Myanmar will not affect the
latter's entry into the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
"We are going to work very hard to get Myanmar into ASEAN," he
told reporters after a function here when asked to comment on the
decision by the Clinton administration to bar new U.S. investments
in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
On whether Malaysia, as the current ASEAN chairman, will
protest against the U.S. decision, Mahathir said his country would
discuss the matter with other ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
On whether the move would affect ASEAN-U.S. relations, Mahathir
said: "No, I don't know. I can't predict what ASEAN is going to
say. We will talk to ASEAN countries."
</P>
<P>
ASEAN foreign ministers are scheduled to meet here on May 31 to
discuss when to admit Myanmar, Cambodia and Laos to the regional
grouping.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN leaders at their informal summit in Jakarta last year
decided on simultaneous admission of all the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is going to host an ASEAN ministerial meeting in July
and an informal ASEAN summit in December.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright announced the ban on new U.S. investment in Myanmar on
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
