<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President on Establishment of New World Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
today called for greater efforts to establish a just and equitable
new world order.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese President made the statement in an address
delivered at Russia's State Duma (lower house).
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the world is moving towards multipolarization, a
hallmark of the present-day international situation.
</P>
<P>
"At both global and regional levels, in both political and
economic arenas, the trend of multipolarization is picking up
speed. The time when a few big powers or power blocs could
monopolize world affairs and dictate the fate of others has gone
for good," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the relations between and among big powers are in
constant shifts and a multitude of power centers is now taking
shape.
</P>
<P>
The developing countries, with increased overall strength and
elevated status, have become an important force on the
international scene to be reckoned with, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Regional organizations of various types are increasingly
active, displaying robust dynamism, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president said though it will still take a long
process for a multipolar world to take place, the trend has
already become an irresistible historical tide which takes on a
crucial significance for the promotion of peace, stability and
development in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said with the end of the Cold War, global forces for peace
have gained strength.
</P>
<P>
"Yes to mutual respect, equality and mutual benefit and no to
hegemonism and power politics. Yes to dialogue and cooperation
and no to confrontation and conflict. This has become the
consensus of more and more countries."
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that in as early as the 1980s, Comrade Deng
Xiaoping, after a scientific analysis of the major and profound
changes in the world, put forth the proposition for the
establishment of a just and equitable new world political order.
</P>
<P>
This initiative of great vision and far-reaching significance
has since been enthusiastically embraced by the international
community.
</P>
<P>
"We in China stand ready to join with statesmen of various
countries in making concerted efforts to promote the establishment
of this new world order," he said.
</P>
<P>
He elaborated that the new world order is based on the Five
Principles of Peaceful Coexistence.
</P>
<P>
"Facts have amply proved that these principles are consistent
with the purposes of the U.N. Charter, perfectly workable in
practice, and reflect the essential characteristics of a new type
of international relations. They have already become universally
recognized norms in international community."
</P>
<P>
Under the new world order, each country has the right to choose
independently its own development path in light of its national
conditions and no other country has the right to interfere in.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the world is a diverse and colorful place, where
countries differ from each other in terms of historical
background, social system, development level, cultural tradition
and values.
</P>
<P>
These differences, he added, instead of posing barriers to the
development of normal state-to-state relations, should serve as
driving forces behind closer exchanges and cooperation of
countries and greater common development and progress.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that imposing one's own social system and ideology
on other countries in international relations is absolutely
unacceptable, and trying to do so will go nowhere.
</P>
<P>
"Only by respecting the independent choices of various peoples,
seeking common ground while setting aside differences and
refraining from interference in each other's internal affairs, can
countries live with each other in harmony and can our world enjoy
genuine peace and tranquillity," he said.
</P>
<P>
All countries, big or small, strong or weak, rich or poor,
should be treated as equal members of the international community
and no country should be allowed to seek hegemony or practice
power politics, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese President said major countries should shoulder
greater responsibility and obligation in maintaining world peace
and stability, reducing armament, promoting development of all
countries and protecting human environment.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, however, this is by no means to suggest that major
countries may dominate the world or enjoy a privilege to
monopolize international affairs.
</P>
<P>
He elaborated that matters that fall within the jurisdiction of
a country's sovereignty should be handled by that country, and
that the affairs of the world should be handled by all the
countries through consultations on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
Under this new world order, countries are called upon to use
peaceful means to settle their differences or disputes, instead of
resorting to the use or threat of force, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that they should increase mutual understanding and
trust through dialogues and consultations and gradually iron out
their differences and problems by way of multilateral or bilateral
coordination and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Cold War mentality and all other practices detrimental to world
peace and development must be resolutely discarded, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under this new international order, countries are urged to
solidify and expand their economic, scientific, technological and
cultural exchanges and cooperation on the basis of equality and
mutual benefit and to promote common development and prosperity,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Unequal and discriminatory policies and practices in economic
and trade relations must be rejected, still less should arbitrary
use of so-called economic sanctions against other countries be
allowed, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The world economy is an interrelated and interdependent
whole. The developing countries need the capital and technology
of the developed countries and the developed countries need the
raw materials and market of the developing countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the developed countries to respect the interests
and needs of the developing countries and increase their economic
input and technical aid to the latter.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if the North-South relations are not improved
and their gap remains wide, it will hurt poor countries and serves
no interest of rich countries either. What is more, it brings no
assurances for world peace and stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0168 </DOCNO>
