<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Development Contributes to Global Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin said
here today that China's development contributes to global peace
and stability.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who is in Russia on a five-day state visit, made the
remarks when delivering a speech at Russia's State Duma (lower
house of parliament).
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese people love and cherish peace. "Having been
subjected to aggression and humiliation by foreign powers for more
than a century in its modern history, China understands full well
how hard-won its peace and independence are."
</P>
<P>
"Our ongoing reform, opening up and modernization drive require
a peaceful international environment. We have always pursued an
independent foreign policy of peace and dedicated ourselves to
maintaining world peace and stability and promoting the common
development of all countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the Chinese Government has stated on many occasions
that China will not participate in arms race, join any military
bloc, or engage in military expansion, nor will it ever seek
hegemony.
</P>
<P>
China has made a unilateral commitment to unconditional
non-first use of nuclear weapons and unconditional non-use or
threat of use of nuclear weapons against non-nuclear states, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that China stands for complete prohibition and
thorough destruction of nuclear weapons and supports the
establishment of nuclear-free zones in Latin America,
Asia-Pacific, Africa and other regions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president said China has provided Ukraine and
Kazakhstan with nuclear security assurances respectively. China
and Russia have announced the mutual detargeting of their nuclear
warheads and mutual non-first use of nuclear weapons against each
other.
</P>
<P>
China, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kirghizstan and Tadzhikistan have
reached an agreement on the reduction of military forces in the
areas along their border of more than 7,000 kilometers, he said.
</P>
<P>
The practice of China's foreign policy fully demonstrates that
China is a positive factor and a strong force in the maintenance
of regional and world peace, he said.
</P>
<P>
"China's development contributes to global stability, and a
prosperous China means a stronger force for peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
History has proved repeatedly that whether a nation poses a
threat to world peace is not determined by its power but by the
nature of its domestic and foreign policies, he added.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that China's domestic policy is one of
wholehearted commitment to socialist modernization and its foreign
policy of independence and peace.
</P>
<P>
"We will not change the fundamental principles underlying these
policies. We will, as always, make unremitting efforts to
safeguard peace in the region and in the world at large," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Growth To Reach 5-6 Percent In 1996-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka should be able to
sustain a growth rate of five to six percent during 1996-2000,
according to a report from the National Economic and Social
Survey.
</P>
<P>
The report said Sri Lanka succeeded in raising its average
economic growth rate from 4.3 percent in 1981-1990 to 5.4 percent
in 1990-1995.
</P>
<P>
Fiscal deficits, however, remained high, which partly explains
the double-digit inflation in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The report said that a structural shift has taken place in the
Sri Lankan economy, especially in the share of GDP produced in
agriculture between 1980 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
During that period, the agricultural share in GDP fell from 26
to 20,  industry rose from 27 to 31 percent and services from 46
to 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka now has a better distributional balance between the
income and population shares of the three sectors with agriculture
employing 35 percent, industry 21 percent and services 44 percent
of the economically active population.
</P>
<P>
The investment rate exceeded 25 percent in Sri Lanka
accompanied by a rise in domestic savings in the 1990s. However
the investment rate could not be sustained as the domestic savings
rate failed to catch up with the investment rate, leaving huge
shortfalls in resources.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's export growth accelerated sharply in 1990-1995 and
as a ratio of growth, GDP exports amounted to nearly 26 percent in
1990-1995 compared to 21 percent in 1985-1989.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that by the year 2020 Sri Lanka's
population, which is 18.5 million at present, will increase by
about 30 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More "Telephone Village" in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Now that telephone lines reach
more than 440,000 households in the Shanghai suburbs, there are
36.6 telephones for every 100 rural families in the area.
</P>
<P>
This average of 11.7 telephones for every 100 local rural
people is much higher than national average of about five for
every 100 persons.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai area now has 1,128 villages where more than 60 percent
of the households have telephones. These "telephone villages" now
account for more than half of the local administrative villages.
</P>
<P>
Rural economic development and income increases for farmers
have encouraged telecommunications bureaus to focus on developing
local villages. Some preferential policies have been made to
encourage local villagers to put in telephones.  
</P>
