<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Using "Crazy" English to Improve Their Language Skills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- About 10,000 people were crowded
into a small outdoor square and were shouting English at the top
of their lungs at the prompting of a leader, to the accompaniment
of wild rock-n-roll music.
</P>
<P>
The scene was not in fact a rock concert, but a live
demonstration given recently to residents in Wuhan, the capital of
central China's Hubei province, of how to improve one's
spoken-English.
</P>
<P>
Li Yang, a former English announcer, invented the new "crazy
English teaching method" to help people establish self-confidence
in language learning by getting them to shout out English
expressions to the sound of loud music.
</P>
<P>
The participants were a mixed band of college students,
businessmen, scholars, and retirees, all of whom showed great
enthusiasm for the new method.
</P>
<P>
One elderly woman, named Yu, said that she had gotten a job
selling computers when she retired, but felt that her
spoken-English was poor when she had to do business with
foreigners. "I get my confidence back when I shout in English to
exciting music," she explained.
</P>
<P>
"It is a successful method, which combines English teaching
with music," commented Mai Wen, who works with the method's
inventor. They held the first of a series of demonstrations in
Shenzhen, in south China's Guangdong province, early this year.
</P>
<P>
Mai explained that they plan to show the new method of English
learning to nearly 300 million Chinese in the next three years,
free of charge, and that demonstrations will be held in 100 cities
nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
