<HEADLINE> Australia to Set Up Tourism Office in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The National Tourism Bureau of
Australia will set up a branch office in China.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed here today by John Morse, chief of the
bureau, at the ongoing 46th annual conference of the Pacific Asia
Travel Association (PATA).
</P>
<P>
"As for the location, we prefer Shanghai," Morse said.
</P>
<P>
China is becoming an increasingly important tourist market for
Australia. Statistics show that in 1996, the number of Chinese
tourists to Australia rose by 27 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Australia predicts that the number of visitors annually from
China will exceed 600,000 in early next century, a figure
surpassing that of Japan, the largest tourist market of Australia
at present.
</P>
<P>
Three airlines now operate flights between China and
Australia: Australian Airlines, Air China, and China Eastern
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
The China Southern Airlines and another Australian air carrier
will also begin the business soon, sources say.
</P>
<P>
Morse said that six out of the ten most important tourist
markets of Australia are in Asia, and the markets are still
expanding rapidly.
</P>
<P>
PATA is a non-governmental tourism organization. Founded in
early 1950s, PATA is holding its annual conference in China for
the first time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
