<HEADLINE> Lebanese Government Decides to Postpone Municipal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 23 (Xinhua) -- In a move designed to save faces
of the country's three top leaders, the Lebanon's government has
set April 30, 1998, as a deadline for holding municipal and
mayoral elections, the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government, which met under President Elias Hrawi at the
Beirut Presidential Palace Tuesday night, charged Interior
Minister Michel Murr with drafting new law for the elections.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the polls, previously scheduled for June 1
and 8 this year, were effectively postponed when Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri withdrew the draft bill from the parliament earlier
this month, thus angering the president who wanted the elections
to take place on time.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi questioned the legality of the retrieval of the bill by
the government without the president's consent.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday night's decisions reflected a comprise that more or
less satisfied each of the troika members, who have been
bickering over a host of issues since last November.
</P>
<P>
The daily noted that the president's candidates for top
administrative posts in three key departments were endorsed,
House Speaker Nabih Berri got the desired eight-month extension
of the parliament's four-year mandate and Hariri won the
postponement of the local elections.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the cabinet's meeting, Information Minister
Bassem al-Sabaa announced that Murr was instructed to draft three
laws, first of which will extend the mandate of current mayors
and municipal councils, due to expire in June, until April 30,
1998.
</P>
<P>
The second decision will regulate local elections and set a
date for them and the third will lengthen the parliament's tenure
to make the next general elections not to fall in the summer of
the year 2000 and disrupt the tourist season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
