<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 6,000 in Shanghai Vow to Donate Organs After Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- While most Shanghai residents
arranged to have their remains cremated, Ma Longrui chose to
donate his organs for medical research after his death.
</P>
<P>
After the old man died at the age of 83, Ma's family offered
his remains to the Shanghai Medical University, according to his
wish, on April 15.
</P>
<P>
Ma became the latest person among some 1,200 in Shanghai, who
have fulfilled their last wishes to donate organs to medical
research institutes after death.
</P>
<P>
Another 5,000 residents in China's largest metropolis have
signed for donation papers since the city's public health
authority and the local Red Cross society jointly called for organ
donation in 1983.
</P>
<P>
The action allowed Shanghai to be a pioneer in organ donation
in China.
</P>
<P>
However, for most Chinese people, organ donation is still
considered unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has a population of 13 million, but the number of
organ donors is only 400, contrasting sharply with some 100,000
people, the annual number of the death in the city.
</P>
<P>
"Pathologic anatomy is vital to research of diseases and to
finding out treatment methods," said Zhou Xiaohan, director of
Oncologic Department, the Shanghai No.1 People's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
"However, we haven't enough bodies of dead patients to conduct
pathologic anatomy because some backward views have prevented
people from donating their bodies to medical research," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Cremation has become popular among Chinese urbanities because
of several decades of reforms. But it may take a long period for
Chinese people to accept organ donation.
</P>
<P>
"So we feel urgent to educate and encourage people to abandon
the backward views and join in the movement," said Xie Lijuan,
president of the Shanghai Red Cross Society.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that well-schooled scientists and office
workers dominated the organ donors in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
In Nanjing, Jiangsu Province's capital city which neighbors
Shanghai, some 500 people have joined in the Friends of Organs
Donors. Many of them were retired government officials and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
They said they decided to become donors after they heard that
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping, who die at the age 93 on February
19, had told his family to donate his corneas to an eye bank and
offer his organs to medical research after his death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
