<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Wetlands Get State Protection For Rare Animals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- More than 20 percent of all the
Yangtze River's white-flag dolphins, an endangered species found
only in China, have settled in the Honghu Lake in Hubei Province,
in central China.
</P>
<P>
The lake has been pollution-free since it was listed as one of
the first wetlands under key state protection in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The wetland is a transitional system between the land ecosystem
and water ecosystem and is the only one with protection from an
international convention. It is regarded as one of three major
ecosystems, along with agricultural and forestry systems, by the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Honghu lake covers more than 35,000 ha and is the largest lake
in Hubei. It is home to 68 species of aquatic plants and 167
species of birds.
</P>
<P>
The National Environmental Protection Agency listed the lake as
one of the first wetlands to be given state protection in 1995. In
the past two years, local authorities have developed measures to
stop enterprises around the lake from polluting and to ban the use
of purse seines.
</P>
<P>
It was approved as the first nature reserve for white-flag
dolphins by the Hubei Provincial Government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
