<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oil Industry Records Sustained Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China's petroleum industry will
enjoy sustainable growth with the maximum annual oil production
probably reaching 200 million tons by 2010.
</P>
<P>
China has achieved great success in "stabilizing the East while
developing the West and offshore," said Gao Ruiqi, director of the
Prospecting Bureau of the China National Petroleum Corporation, at
the World Energy Council Asia Pacific Regional Forum being held in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
China has built 350 oilfields and 110 gasfields, which turned
out 157 million tons of crude oil last year, ranking fifth among
the world oil producers, and produced 20.1 billion cubic meters of
gas, ranking 22nd among the gas producers.
</P>
<P>
After four decades of development, China has built 24 oil and
gas producing bases including Daqing, Shengli, Liaohe, Xinjiang,
Sichuan, Dagang, Bohai, East South China Sea, West South China
Sea, and basically formed the pattern of four major oil and three
major gas producing regions.
</P>
<P>
Among these, the oil output of Songliao region in 1996
accounted for 38 percent of the national total, contributing
greatly to the growth of the national economy. The production of
Bohai Bay in 1996 shared 36.9 percent of the national oil
output. Xinjiang produced 14.3 million tons of crude oil last
year, making up 9.1 percent of the national total. The offshore
production reached 15 million tons, sharing 9.5 percent of the
country's total.
</P>
<P>
According to a national survey, the annual oil output of east
China will maintain 110 million tons in 2010. The annual oil
output of 53 million tons at Daqing Oilfield will be kept until
2000.
</P>
<P>
The exploration will be further accelerated in the west and the
oil output may reach 40-50 million tons in 2010. Offshore oil
production is estimated at 10 million tons or more in 2010.
</P>
<P>
Up to late 1996, the total onshore areas open to foreign
companies reached 2.5 million sq. km. and 30 petroleum contracts
were signed with 35 foreign companies with total volume of 770
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
A total of 109 offshore contracts have been signed with a
foreign capital of 2.96 billion US dollars, which amounts for 58
per cent of the total investment of offshore oil exploration and
development for that period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
