<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Return Spells Closer Regional Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The approaching return of Hong
Kong to China is leading to increased cooperation and exchanges,
as provinces, autonomous regions, and municipalities prepare for
greater business prospects that are inevitable after July 1.
</P>
<P>
"The return will promote economic reorganization in the Pearl
River Delta area and change the structure of the present
factory-shop relations between Guangdong Province and Hong Kong,"
said Xu Dezhi, director of the provincial Commission of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between the two places is indispenable as they are
closely linked economically. Neighboring Guangdong provides water,
electricity, vegetables, and meat to Hong Kong, while 80 percent
of its annual exports and imports come and go through Hong Kong
and Macao and more than 70 percent of its overseas investment
comes from the two.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong will try to become more competitive internationally
through joint efforts with Hong Kong, and make better use of Hong
Kong's role as an international free trade zone, and financial and
information center. Guangzhou Port, in the provincial capital, is
dredging its outbound sealane to a depth of 14.5 meters to
accommodate 50,000-ton freighters in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang Province, which is north of Guangdong in east China,
will hold a Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Fair in late
May in Hong Kong, a sign of cooperation to come between the
coastal province and Hong Kong, said Yang Zucheng, head of the
provincial Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Commission.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been Zhejiang's largest trade partner. Last year,
18.35 percent of its total exports and imports were through Hong
Kong. The province has 30 trade organizations in Hong Kong, and
Hong Kong has been involved in 6,594 projects in Zhejiang, 47.9
percent of the province's total, which are worth 8.8 billion US
dollars, 52.7 percent of the province's total investment.
</P>
<P>
And closer economic ties are also expected between Hong Kong
and other other provinces, autonomous regions, and municipalities
in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Russia Concerned About Enlargement of Military Blocs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China and Russia today expressed
their concern over the attempt at enlarging and strengthening
military blocs.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides (China and Russia) express concern over the attempt
at enlarging and strengthening military blocs, because such a
tendency may pose a threat to the security of certain countries
and aggravate regional and global tension," said a joint statement
signed by the presidents of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Both sides stand for the establishment of a new and universally
applicable security concept, believing that the "Cold War
mentality" must be abandoned and bloc politics opposed, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The differences or disputes between states must be settled
through peaceful means without resorting to the use or threat of
force.
</P>
<P>
"Dialogue and consultation should be pursued to promote mutual
understanding and build confidence, peace and security should be
sought through coordination and cooperation at bilateral or
multilateral level," it said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries stressed the importance of the five-nation
agreements on military confidence and reduction of military forces
in border areas, to be signed by the presidents of China,
Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Russia and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides ... point out that the two Agreements signed by
China, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan on the
Enhancement of Confidence in the Military Field Along the Border
Areas and on the Mutual Reduction of Military Forces are of great
significance in that they may serve as a new model for the
achievement of regional peace, security and stability in the
post-Cold War world," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
China and Russia also vowed to promote the disarmament process
in the world.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides stand ready to promote the disarmament process
while emphasizing the importance of the signing of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and the implementation of the
Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin is in Russia for a five-day state
visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
