<HEADLINE> China, Russia Vow to Push for New World Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China and Russia said in a joint
statement today that they will strive to promote the
multipolarization of the world and the establishment of a new
world order.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides (China and Russia) shall, in the spirit of
partnership, strive to promote the multipolarization of the world
and the establishment of a new international order," said the
joint statement, signed today by Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a just and equitable new international
political and economic order based on peace and stability has
become the pressing need of the times and the inevitable necessity
of history, it said.
</P>
<P>
The document noted that international relations at the close of
the 20th century have undergone profound changes characterized by
the end of the Cold War and the disappearance of the bipolarity,
each represented by the United States and the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
The positive trend toward a multipolar world is accelerating,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between major powers, including those between
adversaries in the Cold War era, have undergone changes;
organizations of regional economic cooperation have exhibited
great vitality; the political, economic and cultural evolution in
various countries has presented a scene of diversity, and the
forces working for peace and broad-based international cooperation
have grown in strength, it continued.
</P>
<P>
"It has become the common understanding of a growing number of
countries to embrace mutual respect, equality and mutual benefit
and reject hegemonism and power politics, to pursue dialogue and
cooperation and avoid confrontation and conflict," the statement
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
