<HEADLINE> Uganda Fixes New Power Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A new power line is being fixed
between Owen Falls Hydroelectric Station and Kampala, to help
improve power distribution in Uganda's capital city.
</P>
<P>
The local daily New Vision reported today that the 20-Million
-U.S.-Dollar project is funded by Danish Development Agency
(DANIDA) and the construction is done by Phil Colas, an
international construction firm.
</P>
<P>
The Pylon construction for the power distribution line has so
far reached eastern part of Kampala, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The line has a capacity of 300 megawatts, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Kampala consumes about 60 percent of power generation of the
Owen Falls station with an installed capacity of 150 megawatts,
is the sole hydroelectric station in the country currently.
</P>
<P>
The construction of a separate line for Kampala is aimed at
serving the city well, Uganda Electricity Board boss, Simon
d'Ujanga was quoted as saying. 
</P>
