<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long-Distance Medical Network In East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Long-Distance Medical
Network now has a branch at Zhongshan Hospital in Xiamen, in the
eastern province of Fujian.
</P>
<P>
Patients on this island city will have access to expert medical
help in Shanghai, which lies some 1,000 km to the north, via the
network.
</P>
<P>
Using multi-media computers and a teleconferencing system, the
network can connect major medical centers, hospitals, clinics, and
families and can transmit a patient's medical history, data,
cardiograms, ultrasound pictures, X-rays, and CT scans to hospitals
outside the province.
</P>
<P>
Doctors can develop a plan of treatment by analyzing the
information and by consulting colleagues or even the patients
directly. The system allows doctors thousands of miles away to
make a diagnosis similar to one that they would have made on the
spot, all within a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
The system was jointly developed by Zhongshan Hospital in
Xiamen, Zhongshan Hospital attached to the Shanghai Medical
College, and the Shanghai Long-distance Medicare Network Research
and Development Center.
</P>
<P>
This is the first and only long-distance medical system in
China at present. It is operating in more than 40 cities around
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
