<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Golden Monkeys Give Birth in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Three golden monkeys at the
Beijing Breeding Center for Endangered Animals have recently given
birth to three babies that are doing well, according to workers.
</P>
<P>
China has three types of golden monkey, classified according to
their geographic locations. The three are found mainly in Sichuan,
Yunnan and Guizhou provinces in southwest China and in Shaanxi and
Gansu provinces in northwest China. The mothers are the Sichuan
type.
</P>
<P>
Golden monkeys are under Class-A government protection. The
monkeys have beautiful fine hair and live in mountainous areas,
from 1,500 to 3,800 m above sea level. They mate in late fall, and
have a gestation period of six months, giving birth to one
offspring. They are sexually mature at four or six years of age
and have a life expectancy of 16 to 18 years.
</P>
<P>
The survival rate of baby monkeys is very low under artificial
conditions. In the past decade, the Beijing Breeding Center, which
was set up in 1987, has succeeded in breeding 20 golden monkeys,
increasing the number at the center from 11 to more than 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
