<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 07:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Attorney-General Joins Campaign Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Former Israeli
Attorney-General Michael Ben-Yair has joined a campaign to demand
a state inquiry into the state prosecution's decision to drop
charges against Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Following the Sunday announcement by current Attorney-General
Elyakim Rubinstein not to indict Netanyahu and Justice Minister
Tzahi Hanegbi for their involvement in the Bar-On scandal,
opponents to the decision immediately formed an organization to
demand that a state inquiry commission be set up to probe the
whole affair.
</P>
<P>
The group organized a demonstration Tuesday night opposite
the Knesset (Parliament), which was attended by Ben-Yair and
several other notables. Ben-Yair, who was appointed by former
Labor Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, resigned in early last
December after being repeatedly attacked by the Likud government
as an political opponent.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Yair's resignation led to the controversial appointment of
former Jerusalem attorney Roni Bar-On as his successor on
January 10. Bar-On's short-lived appointment was later exposed as
a political scandal that involved Netanyahu who allegedly made a
deal with Shas party leader Aryeh Deri, who pushed for Bar-On's
apppointment in hope to obtain a plea bargain deal in his
bribery trial. The state prosecution has announced that Deri was
to be charged with extortion and fraud.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Yair said that only a state inquiry commission, headed by
the High Court of Justice, could provide the public with the
whole truth of what took place in the Bar-On affair. "Without
this the public will lose faith in the current government," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Yair's stand drew a sharp retort from the Likud, which in
a statement denounced him as a man "harboring undisguised
hostility toward the Likud." The statement said that Ben-Yair
himself was a "much-criticized political appointee," who while
in office deliberately dropped indictments against leading
Laborites charged with corruption and elections fraud.
</P>
<P>
This was referring to Bene-Yair's decision to drop charges
against former Labor ministers Binyamin Ben-Eliezer and Yisrael
kessar as well as several Labor lawmakers for their roles in the
1992 Knesset election and 1994 Histadrut (General Trade Union)
election.
</P>
<P>
After Netanyahu's Likud government came to power last June,
Ben-Yair put Likud's Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert on trial for
irregularities in the Likud campaign for the 1988 Knesset
election. He also ordered a police investigation against former
Justice Minister Yaacov Neeman, who was forced to resign last
August.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition Labor and Meretz lawmakers continued
their campaign to topple the Netanyahu government over the
Bar-On scandal. Meretz lawmaker Anat Maor and Labor lawmaker
Dalia Itzik have begun collecting the signatures of 40 lawmakers
needed to convene the Knesset to discuss removing Netanyahu from
office.
</P>
<P>
Raanan Cohen, chairman of Labor's Knesset faction, is
requesting that the Knesset State Control Committee meet this
week to discuss establishing a state inquiry commission into the
Bar-On scandal.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Meretz leader Yossi Sarid and three other Labor
lawmakers submitted petitions to the High Court to overturn the
state prosecution's decision not to indict Netanyahu and other
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
