<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Shoots up to 17.5 Percent in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Inflation rate as measured
by the Consumer Price Index (CPI) increased from 12.8 percent in
February to 17.5 percent in March this year in Tanzania, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by a report of the National Consumer Price
index released by the Bureau of Statistics covering the period
from March 15 to April 15, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The CPI indicates that the rate of increase in general level
of prices of mass consumption goods rose by 4.7 percent in a
month.
</P>
<P>
This is the first upward trend in one year as inflation
steadily dropped from 26 percent in December 1995 and almost
reached single-digit level in February this year.
</P>
<P>
The upsurge in the price levels has been attributed by Bureau
of Statistics in the Planning Commission to a big increase
recorded by the food group index for a wide range of products
including rice, maize grain, maize flour, beans, cow peas, fruits
and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Experts observed that the food group prices increased by 17.2
percent, which carries a weight of 72 percent in the consumer
basket were the major cause of spiraling inflation.
</P>
<P>
The experts said distribution bottle necks creating food
shortages in major urban markets was responsible for the increase
in the general level of food prices.
</P>
<P>
However, it is noted that from last October to March this
year, Tanzania experienced the worst drought in the last four
decades, and the country is at present facing serious food
shortage.
</P>
<P>
According to an official report, a total of 138,765 tons of
food are needed for about four million Tanzanians facing an acute
food shortage in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
