<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economy Improves In Chinese Revolutionary Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Yan'an, in northwest China's
Shaanxi Province, which was one of the country's poorest places,
hit a new high last year in sustaining itself when per capita
income of farmers rose to 1,100 yuan and per capita grain
production to 509 kg.
</P>
<P>
The area was the most important revolutionary base in China,
from which Mao Zedong and his colleagues fought the Anti-Japanese
War (1937-1945) and the Liberation War (1945-1949). But, its
remote location and harsh geographical conditions kept it from
developing.
</P>
<P>
But its location on the Loess Plateau turned out to be rich in
mineral resources. Proven reserves of oil there amounted to 430
million tons, of gas 3.3 billion cm, and of coal 7.1 billion tons.
</P>
<P>
The local government has lately focused on developing
resource-related industries, and as a result, petrochemistry,
coal, and electricity have become the city's pillar industries,
contributing greatly to its industrial and financial growth, which
now ranks first among the province's 10 prefectures and cities,
according to Gao Yixin, the city's party secretary. And years of
hard work by its 1.8 million residents has improved its
infrastructure considerably. Villages are now linked by both paved
roads and telephones.
</P>
<P>
In agriculture, the city has concentrated on planting tobacco,
fruit trees, potatoes, and sheep breeding, opening up nearly two
ha of land per capita. These four agricultural industries had 1.36
billion yuan in output value last year, accounting for 70 percent
of its total agricultural production, and providing food and
clothing for 130,000 poor people in the area.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, Yan'an will be a base for exporting
apples, production and processing of potatoes, flue-cured tobacco,
energy, and petrochemistry -- and educating citizens about China's
revolutionary tradition, Gao noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Delegation Visits Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of the Nigerian
government, led by Foreign Affairs Minister Chief Tom Ikimi, is
in Liberia for a five-day assessment visit, the Daily Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will assess the preparations being made by
Liberia's Independent Electoral Commission for the formulation of
electoral laws, voters registration, education and activities so
as to ensure a free and fair legislative and presidential poll.
</P>
<P>
The delegation left the Nigerian capital of Abuja on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The elections are scheduled for May 30 and the assessment
visit is the last to be undertaken before the elections.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria now holds the chairmanship of the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS) of which Liberia is a member.
</P>
</TEXT>
