<HEADLINE> Israel Launches Campaign Round up Hamas Activists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli security forces have
unleashed a sweeping crackdown on the activists of the Islamic
Resistance Movement, or Hamas, in the West Bank over the past few
days, according to the state-run Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of the activists have been reportedly arrested. Israeli
troops searched mosques, charity bodies, health institutions and
schools under the pretext of preempting terrorist attacks during
the week-long Jewish Passover holiday.
</P>
<P>
In Nablus alone, at least eight people, mostly students at
An Najah University in Nablus, were arrested. Jamal Mansour,
Hamas spokesman from Nablus, told foreign reporters that the
arrest took place during the Eid al-Adha holiday.
</P>
<P>
Mansour said Hamas would not stop its attacks against
Israel until Israel stopped "its measures against Hamas and the
Palestinian people."
</P>
<P>
Mansour, who met Monday with Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat, said that Arafat has plans to hold talks
abroad with Hamas leaders and with opposition leaders George
Habash, head of the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine, and Nayef Hawatmeh, head of of the Democratic Front
for the Liberation of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Dr. Abdel-Aziz Rantisi, who was spokesman for
the 400 Islamic radicals deported by Israel to south Lebanon
in 1992, said in a newspaper interview Tuesday that the
failure of the Oslo process means that Hamas has judged well
and it has no plans to change its political or military
strategy toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
The senior Hamas official, who was released from Beesheba
Prison on Sunday night after serving a 40-month sentence imposed
upon his return in December 1993, called for a continuation of
the intifada (uprising) "which began with stones and never ended,
but developed and continues to develop with new methods that Hamas
is using."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Al-Quds, a Jerusalem Arabic daily, Rantisi said
that: "Hamas today has never been stronger."
</P>
<P>
He did not speak directly about violent attacks and suicide
bombings, but stated clearly that he supported them. "We are
not for useless sacrifices, which would be the case if we
were sending martyrs to Hell, but we were sending them to
Paradise," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
