<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't, Rebel Group Suspend Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The peace panels of the Philippine
government and the rebel National Democratic Front have decided to
suspend their ongoing talks due to conflicting positions on the
manner of implementing an agreement they are going to sign.
</P>
<P>
The government panel said in a press statement today that the
two sides made the decision after holding intensive negotiations
on April 19-22 in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The two sides started their talks in the Netherlands earlier
this year and were reported to have made progress towards signing
an accord on human rights and international humanitarian law and
three other agreements.
</P>
<P>
Their talks on human rights and international humanitarian law
have reached a point where they must specify the mode of the
implementation and reject any ambiguous language that could be
interpreted as conferring equal sovereign status on the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The government panel made it clear that the mode of
implementation should be in accordance with the constitutional and
legal processes of the country, but this was rejected by the rebel
side.
</P>
<P>
The National Democratic Front argued that the government
panel's proposal is a violation of the joint Hague Declaration
signed by both parties in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The government panel, however, defended its position that the
declaration, based on mutually acceptable principles, does not
mean that the government diminished its sovereignty in seeking a
principled end to the armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
Because the mode of implementation affects all four
comprehensive agreements, the two sides decided not to continue
their negotiations until this fundamental issue has been resolved,
the statement said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
