<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Economy Forecast To Sustain High Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian economy will
sustain its high growth rate during the next two years, according
to a report released by the Malaysian Institute of Economic
Research (MIER) today.
</P>
<P>
The country's economy was projected to maintain a stable growth
rate of 8.2 percent in 1997 and is forecast to grow further to 8.5
percent in 1998, MIER said in its Malaysian Economic Update for
the first quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's real gross domestic product (GDP) was 8.2 percent in
1996.
</P>
<P>
MIER said private consumption should remain relatively robust
with growth projected at 7.6 percent for 1997 and 8.1 percent in
1998 against 8.0 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The private think tank said that with an anticipated recovery
in the export sector and rapid expansion of domestic activities,
private sector investment would grow at a brisk pace at 13.8
percent for 1997 and at 13.6 percent for 1998 in comparison with a
7.2 percent in 1996. Public investment would also be strong.
</P>
<P>
Exports of goods and non-factor services would grow by 7.0
percent in 1997 and 12.9 percent in 1998 compared with 7.8 percent
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports of goods and non-factor services would grow
at 8.9 percent in 1997 and 13.5 percent in 1998 against 6.0
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit was projected at 14.3 billion
ringgit (about 5.72 billion U.S. dollar). The merchandise balance
was forecast to record a slightly lower surplus of 8.1 billion
ringgit (about 3.24 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, but would
improve to 10.2 billion ringgit (about 4.08 billion U.S. dollars)
in 1998, MIER said.
</P>
<P>
Monetary policy is expected to remain tight for the whole of
1997 while downside risk of a slightly deteriorating current
account deficit could not be overlooked, MIER said.
</P>
<P>
The underlying inflationary pressure would remain with
inflation expected to stand at 3.7 percent in both 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
The labor market would continue to tighten further with
unemployment forecast at 2.5 percent in 1997 and further down to
2.4 percent in 1998 compared with 2.6 percent in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
