<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves 190 million USD Loan to Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today approved
a loan of 190 million U.S. dollars to finance two Brazilian
projects on land reform and natural resources management.
</P>
<P>
Ninety million dollars will go to the Land Reform and Poverty
Alleviation Project. This will benefit 15,000 poor farmers in the
northeastern states of Brazil, who are currently without land or
do not have enough land to provide for the subsistence needs of
their families.
</P>
<P>
The project, scheduled to be completed on June 30, 2001, will
help the government accelerate its land reform program.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost a total of 150 million dollars and will
get the remaining funds from the Brazilian federal and state
governments and the benefiting communities.
</P>
<P>
A Natural Resources Management Project for the state of Rio
Grande do Sul, in Brazil, will receive 100 million U.S. dollars
from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to improve management of the state's natural
resources in an area of about three million hectares with about
112,000 small farmers. It will increase access to basic social and
income-generating infrastructure services for about 98,000 poor
rural households.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of this project is about 208.4 million dollars,
and the Brazilian government will make up the rest of the money.
</P>
</TEXT>
