<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Toy Exports to Europe Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's exports of wooden and
soft toys to Europe have been increasing considerably during
recent years, according to the Export Development Board (EDB) here
today.
</P>
<P>
EDB sources said the value of Sri Lankan toy exports to Europe
went up from 32.32 million U.S. dollars in 1992 to 68.11 million
dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The rise is attributed to Sri Lanka's participation in various
international toy fairs under a promotion campaign by the EDB.
</P>
<P>
This year, Sri Lankan toy exporters received orders worth
352.14 million dollars at the Nuremberg International Toy Fair '97
in Germany held recently. Several other orders are under
negotiation, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
There are 75 established toy exporters in Sri Lanka, of whom 50
are wooden toy and 15 soft toy exporters. The wooden toy sector in
Sri Lanka has a long history while the soft toy one is something
new.
</P>
<P>
The sources noted that the Sri Lankan toy sector needs a lot of
encouragement as local raw materials such as rubber wood could be
used and employment opportunities created for people even in rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
Major markets for Sri Lankan toys are Germany, the Netherlands,
Britain, Japan, Australia, the United States and the Scandinavian
countries, the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
