<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 60 Percent of AIDS Victims Dead Within 14 Years in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Sixty percent of the 49,500
Mexicans infected with the AIDS virus over the last 14 years have
died, figures released today from the National Council for the
Control and Prevention of Aids (Conasida) show.
</P>
<P>
Some 29,700 people have died of AIDS since 1983. But Consida
said that the growth in the number of new cases of people with the
HIV virus was slowing down and was now at between 3,000 to 4,000 a
year, an annual increase of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
But Consida said that based on these figures, and on the
premise that for each recorded case four go unrecorded, the number
of AIDS victims in Mexico could be as high as 200,000.
</P>
<P>
In 1994 the death rate from AIDS in Mexico was 3.9 percent for
every 100,000 inhabitants while in 1996 it rose to 4.4 percent,
thus placing AIDS in 16th place as a cause of death.
</P>
<P>
The figures were released to co-incide with the launch of a
four-year program to step up the prevention and control of
HIV, AIDS and other sexually-transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
Figures indicate that HIV Infection rate through blood
transfusions has shown a marked decrease, from 17 percent in 1989
to 8.3 at present. The infection rate among prostitutes is 0.04
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
