<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Fights Transport Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The two-day meeting of the
European transport ministers ended today in Berlin with approval
of a resolution to fight smuggling and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
German Transport Minister Matthias Wissmann said transport
crime among European Union countries caused losses of one billion
marks (about 580 million U.S. dollars) during the period, 1990 to
1994. In 1995, German losses amounted to 21 million marks (12
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The meeting aimed at working out a transport policy and
strategy to combat rising transport crime in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said European countries would improve
conditions for information and data exchanges to ensure police
could take rapid action against criminals.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also discussed transport conditions between east
and west European countries, and agreed to resolve the problem of
traffic congestion, especially in border areas.
</P>
<P>
Thirty European transport ministers attended the meeting. The
next one will be held in Copenhagen, Denmark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
