<HEADLINE> Nepali Capital Beefs up Security as Crime on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Police are taking new
measures to tighten security in this capital city as the crime
rate rose over 12.6 percent in the past year, a senior police
officer said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Inspector General of Police Dhalman Thapa told a press
conference here Tuesday that a new security plan has been devised
by the police to control the increasing criminal activities,
especially sex services and hooliganism in a tourist-oriented area
of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Under the new provisions, mobile police teams will be set up to
patrol some main crossroads and particular areas in downtown
Kathmandu and all the police offices in the city will be open
around the clock, the police officer said.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters on the new forms of crimes in Kathmandu
during recent months, Thapa said that the crime of vehicle theft
from private houses and parking areas was on the rise and the
stolen cars were often deserted by the criminals after being used
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
Another form of theft on the rise was related with breaking
into locked houses after pelting stones at the windowpanes, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
