<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru's Rescue Operation Praised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto on Wednesday praised Peru for freeing Japan's 24
hostages in Lima, but regretted that Tokyo had not been informed
in advance, reports said.
</P>
<P>
All of the Japanese captives, 12 businessmen and 12 diplomats,
were rescued safely, Hashimoto said in televised speech from his
office, after the assault on the Japanese ambassador's residence
by a 150-strong Peruvian strike team ended a four-month-long
standoff with rebels in Lima.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to thank (Peruvian) President (Alberto) Fujimori
and the Peruvian government for carrying out a splendid rescue,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"I want to rejoice together that they (the hostages) are all
safe," he said.
</P>
<P>
One hostage and two soldiers were killed in the assault, along
with the 14 hostage-takers, reports from Lima quoted Fujimori as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Hashimoto said that Japan was "regrettable" that
it had not been informed of the raid beforehand. "But I understand
(the decision of the Peruvian government)," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the four-month long crisis, Japan had repeatedly asked
Fujimori to avoid measures that might endanger the lives of the
captives.
</P>
<P>
Now with the crisis over, Hashimoto defended Fujimori's
actions. "Now that all the hostages were safely freed, no one can
blame Fujimori for using force (to settle the crisis)," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said the
United States had some "indications" in advance that Peruvian armed
forces were preparing to storm the Japanese ambassador's residence
in Lima, but received no prior word officially.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. played virtually no role," Cohen said in an interview
with CNN.
</P>
<P>
At the White House, spokesman Eric Rubin said the U.S. has
taken the position that the rebels bear "full responsibility for
this crisis. We have stated that the Peruvian government was right
not to make concessions to terrorists."
</P>
<P>
And in Ottawa, Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy said on
Tuesday that Canada had preferred peaceful means to end the Lima
hostage crisis, but nonetheless supported the result, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
"We would have...preferred to see the resolution take place by
more peaceful means, but that was simply a preference," Axworthy
told reporters after the raid on the Japanese ambassador's
residence began.
</P>
<P>
The armed Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA) guerrillas
stormed the Japanese Ambassador Morihisa Aoki's residence in Lima
on December 17 during a cocktail party marking Japanese emperor's
birthday and took almost 500 guests hostage.
</P>
<P>
They released most of the hostages later, but had held 72 male
captives to press their demand for the release of their jailed
comrades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
