<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan to Merge Poor Areas to Boost Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan's President Nursultan
Nazarabyev today signed a decree merging two of the country's
poorest districts into other administrative to try to boost their
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The move, which will cut the number of administrative districts
from 19 to 17, is part of the government's attempts at social,
economic and administrative reform, Kazakh Prime Minister Akezhan
Kazhegeldin said at a news conference this evening.
</P>
<P>
Turgai district will be merged into Aqmolo and Kustanai, and
Taldy-Kurgan will be merged into Alma-Ata district.
</P>
<P>
The two districts are the two most backward areas in the
country, accounting for only 1.3 percent and 1.5 percent of the
country's total output, and their economic prospects are
deteriorating rapidly, Kazhegeldin said.
</P>
<P>
A task force headed by first Deputy Prime Minister Akhmetzhan
Esimov and Deputy Prime Minister Zanybek Karibzanov has been set
up to handle the integration, Kazhegeldin added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
