<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangkok to Crack Down on Sales of Contaminated Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Food and Drug Administration
(FDA) of Thailand and the Bangkok Metropolitan Administration will
start a city-wide crackdown on supermarkets and stores which sell
contaminated and substandard food.
</P>
<P>
About 300 officials from the two organizations will carry out
random checks on packaged food at city department stores and
supermarkets from next week.
</P>
<P>
The FDA and Bangkok authorities will also seek cooperation from
owners and operators of about 600 supermarkets and stores in
Bangkok in eliminating contaminated and substandard, packaged food
from their shelves.
</P>
<P>
All packaged food is required to bear a label giving details
about the manufacturer, date of manufacture, expiration date and
use of preservatives, according to Bangkok Governor Bhichit
Rattakul.
</P>
<P>
Anyone selling packaged food contaminated with dangerous
substances and bacteria is subject to a maximum fine of 20,000
baht (800 U.S. dollars) and up to two years in prison under the
Food and Drug Act.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok authorities are also empowered to revoke the
operating license of stores found selling contaminated food.
</P>
<P>
Anyone selling unlabeled packaged food will face a maximum fine
of 30,000 baht (1,200 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Over the last few months, some Bangkok supermarkets have been
found selling food containing chemicals used to keep corpse from
decaying and harmful artificial coloring.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
