<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Complete National Car Program by 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government said
its national car program would be over by the time a Japanese
complaint was ruled on by the World Trade Organization (WTO) in
1999.
</P>
<P>
Industry and Trade Minister Tunky Ariwibowo said here Tuesday
night after attending a limited cabinet meeting that he was
optimistic Indonesia's national car program would be completed by
1999 when the car would have a local parts content of 60 percent
-- a hurdle which allows all autos similar tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto ruled in February 1996 that producers of a
national car would be granted exemptions on import duties and
luxury taxes, which add about 60 percent to the price of other
cars in the country.
</P>
<P>
Pt. Timor Putra Nasional (TPN) controlled by the president's
youngest son Hutomo Mandala Putra was chosen as the first national
car supplier and is required to clear an eventual 60 percent local
content goal by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Tunky said the government would provide whatever assistance TPN
needed to finish the program by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Last October, Japan, the European Union and the United States
filed separate complaints with the WTO over the policy which they
say is discriminatory and violates WTO rules.
</P>
<P>
Japan, after months of bilateral negotiations with Indonesia,
decided last week to take the issue to a WTO panel later this
month.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto Monday ordered an end to bilateral
negotiations on the issue with Japan and said Indonesia will
continue to produce the Timor national car despite pressure from
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Tunky will go to Japan today on a four-day trade mission but he
will not discuss the car issue during the visit, official sources
said today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
