<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ninth Summit Meeting of Andean Group Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUCRE, BOLIVIA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Closer ties with other
regional blocs, free trade and reform are top of the agenda of a
two-day summit between the presidents of the four-nation
free-trade zone of the Andean Group.
</P>
<P>
These three fundamental issues are included in a draft of the
Sucre Act, the main document of the summit, which is due to be
signed later today by the presidents of Bolivia, Ecuador, Colombia
and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The Sucre Act also proposes the institutionalization of a
dialogue between the group and China, and a strategy of
association with South America's biggest trade bloc Mercosur, of
which Bolivia is already an associate member.
</P>
<P>
The presidents will also discuss how to persuade Peru, which
quit the organization in early April, to rejoin. Peru announced
on April 12 that it would leave the group, claiming it was still
limiting free and fair trade.
</P>
<P>
Its decision came in the wake of the refusal by other members
to grant Peru exemptions from the free-trade regime. Peru also
accused those members which had already implemented a duty-free
policy of subsidizing their exports to Peru.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the summit, Ecuadoran President
Fabrian Alarcon stressed the need to transform the Andean Group
into an authentic free trade zone to push forward regional
integration.
</P>
<P>
He said Andean countries could not remain isolated. They must
remain united as this was the only way to take advantage of the
enormous market potential in South America and in the regions of
other trade blocs.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the summit, Bolivian President Gonzalo Sanchez de
Lozada said that the Andean Group would seek closer ties with
Asia-Pacific countries.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian President Ernesto Prez Balladares and Paraguayan
President Juan Carlos Wasmosy are taking part in the summit as
guests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
