<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Emergency Post-Conflict Assistance to Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved a loan for Rwanda equivalent to some 12
million U.S. dollars under its emergency post-conflict assistance,
to back the government's economic program for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The program covers a transitional phase which could lead to the
adoption of a medium-term strategy eligible for loans under the
fund's Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF).
</P>
<P>
The strategy is aimed at promoting the economic and social
reintegration of over two million former refugees and fostering
economic and financial recovery.
</P>
<P>
The tiny African country's economy was devastated in 1994 after
a wide-spread a conflict between the Hutu-led government and the
Tutsi-led rebels of the Rwandan Patriotic Front.
</P>
<P>
The turmoil resulted in a genocide in which a total of 500,000
Rwandese were killed and five million became refugees .
</P>
<P>
The main plank of Rwanda's reform efforts this year will be
fiscal consolidation through a reduction in the budget deficit
from 2.7 percent of GDP in 1996 to 0.9 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Budgetary revenue is projected to increase by about 26 percent
to the equivalent of 10.3 percent of GDP, while expenditure will
be allowed to increase by only 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda joined the IMF in September 1963. Its quota is about 81
million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF credit currently
stands at about 23 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
