<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Agricultural Expansion in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today approved
a 125 million U.S. dollar loan for a Provincial Agriculture
Development Project in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to increase and diversify agriculture
production and exports and to improve the productivity of land use
by introducing new technologies and modern varieties of existing
crops. It will also help increase and stabilize the incomes of
some 120,000 small-and medium-sized farms.
</P>
<P>
Argentina has a total of some 420,000 farms across the country,
nearly half of which are smaller than 50 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Sub-projects already approved to be financed by the loan
include the development of the Colorado River Valley in the
province of Buenos Aires, irrigation and drainage in Montecaseros,
province of Mendoza and the Medndoza provincial irrigation
program, flood control in Pozo Borrado in the province of Santa Fe
and others.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is some 357.2 million dollars. In
addition to the World Bank loan, another 125 million loan will be
provided by the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB), 90 million
dollars coming from Argentine federal and provincial funds and
17.2 million dollars from beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
The project will be implemented over a seven year period.
</P>
</TEXT>
