<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (39-40) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (39-40)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Who has the power of final adjudication in Hong Kong
after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Before 1997, under British colonial rule, Hong Kong has
applied British laws and a British legal system. Lawsuits are
routed, according to different categories and classes, to
magistrates' courts, districts courts and the High Court.
</P>
<P>
However, Hong Kong has never had the power of final
adjudication. The court of final appeal is in the British Privy
Council.
</P>
<P>
After 1997, to ensure that the Hong Kong SAR have a high degree
of autonomy and full and independent judicial power, the Basic Law
stipulates that the Hong Kong SAR be vested with the power of
final adjudication except for cases concerning national
territorial integrity, national defence, diplomacy and relations
between the central authorities and the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Lawsuits within the Hong Kong SAR may be subject to final
adjudication by the Court of Final Adjudication of the Hong Kong
SAR.
</P>
<P>
Question: How will the judiciary of the Hong Kong SAR be
established?
</P>
<P>
Answer: After 1997, the judicial system previously practised in
Hong Kong will be maintained except fro those changes compelled by
the establishedment of the Court of Final Appeal of the Hong Kong
SAR.
</P>
<P>
That is to say, the current judicial system of Hong Kong will
remain basically unchanged after 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, "basically unchanged" does not mean no change at
all. The most important change is seen in the relationship between
the Hong Kong courts and the British Privy Council.
</P>
<P>
Before 1997, the power of final adjudication goes to the
British Privy Council. After 1997, a Court of Final Appeal will be
established in the Hong Kong SAR to exercise the power of final
adjudication.
</P>
<P>
This not only abolishes a judiciary system with strong colonial
features, but also represents Hong Kong's high degree of autonomy
under Chinese sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the Court of Final Appeal, to be established in the
Hong Kong SAR will be the High Court, district courts,
magistrates' courts and other special courts. The High Court
consists of the Court of Appeal and the Court of First Instance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Peru Hostage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The four-month hostage standoff in
Lima was ended today, after the Peruvian troops stormed the Japanese
ambassador's residence in Lima, freeing 71 of the 72 hostages, and
leaving one captive, two soldiers and the 14 MRTA captors dead.
</P>
<P>
The following is a chronology of the main events during the
126-day crisis:
</P>
<P>
April 22 -- Peruvian troops stormed the Japanese ambassador's
residence in Lima, freeing all the hostages and thus ending the
prolonged crisis.
</P>
<P>
April 17 -- Cuban Foreign Minister visited Tokyo to cooperate
with Japan in ending the crisis by agreeing to accept the MRTA
rebels.
</P>
<P>
April 10 -- Organization of American States (OAS) General
Secretary Cesar Gaviria announced in San Jose "unconditional
support" to Peruvian President Alberto Fijimori.
</P>
<P>
March 18-20 -- Japan's Vice-Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura
visited Peru, Cuba and the Dominican Republic. He received formal
agreements from Havana and Santo Domingo to give the
hostage-takers asylum.
</P>
<P>
March 12 -- The two sides held 10th round of talks, agreeing to
a period of reflection.
</P>
<P>
March 6 -- Negotiations were suspected after MRTA rebels
accused Peruvian authorities of digging a tunnel in an attempt to
storm the besieged Japanese ambassador's residence.
</P>
<P>
March 5 -- Ninth round of talks was held where the two sides
exchanged formal proposals.
</P>
<P>
March 3 -- Fujimori made a surprise trip to Cuba where
President Fidel Castro offered to grant asylum to rebels if all
sides agreed.
</P>
<P>
March 2 -- Fujimori flew to the Dominican Republic to discuss
possible asylum for the guerrillas if there was a peaceful
settlement to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Feb. 17 -- Sixty-second day of standoff, beating Latin
America's previous longest hostage siege: a 61-day seizure of the
Dominican Embassy in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Feb. 11 -- Talks restarted in a safe house opposite the
ambassador's residence.
</P>
<P>
Feb. 1 -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and
Fujimori met in Toronto. The two agreed to push for direct talks
with rebels.
</P>
<P>
Jan. 1, 1997 -- Rebels released seven captives, lowering
hostage total to 74.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 28 -- Government negotiator Domingo Palermo entered the
residence for face-to-face negotiations with the rebels. The
rebels released 20 hostages.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 22 -- Rebels freed 225 hostages not linked to the
government.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 20 -- Rebels freed 38 hostages.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 19 -- Four ambassadors were released to be a
"communications channel" between the rebels and the government.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 18 -- The rebels threatened to kill their hostages unless
the Peruvian government frees about 400 jailed comrades.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 17, 1996 -- Some 20 heavily armed rebels captured hundreds
of guests of the Japanese ambassador in his residence but they
freed all women and some elderly men soon after the attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trans-Mekong Road Corridor to Gain Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A proposed plan on building an
east-west road corridor traversing the Greater Mekong Region (GMS)
is expected to gain speed after Thailand, Laos and Vietnam have
agreed to push it ahead.
</P>
<P>
The corridor, which will link Malamang in Myanmar, Mae Sot in
Tak province and Mukdahan in Mukdahan province in Thailand,
Savannakhet in Laos, and Danang in Vietnam, is designed to provide
a land short-cut between the Indian and Pacific oceans to
facilitate flows of goods.
</P>
<P>
The three countries made the decision to push the project at a
GMS ministerial meeting last week in Manila, according to
officials from the Thai National Economic and Social Development
Board.
</P>
<P>
They are seeking funds for the project from international
lending institutions, especially the Asian Development Bank, local
newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
The Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund from Japan has agreed to
offer 20 million U.S. dollars in soft loans to finance the
project, which includes the upgrading of the ports at Malamang and
Danang.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government also is expected to provide 500 million
baht (20 million dollars) to help build the road section within
Thailand. the Thai government earlier had agreed to finance
one-half of the construction cost for a bridge at Mukdahan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the World Bank will finance Vietnam for building
the section of the highway running from the Laotian border to
Danang.
</P>
<P>
However, Myanmar has not made any decision to push the project
due to the political situation in the country, local newspapers
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0251 </DOCNO>
