<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Fair Snares Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese exporters clinched
deals worth 3.067 billion US dollars during the first seven days
of the 81st Chinese Export Commodities Fair, up 20.09 percent over
the corresponding week of last spring's fair, today's "China
Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper uses the latest fair statistics as
that light industrial products and handicraft articles won the lion's
share of the export contracts, hitting 865 million US dollars,
27.48 percent more than during the same period of the spring fair
last year.
</P>
<P>
Machinery and electronics product orders were up 83.61 percent
hitting 851 million US dollars. Sales contracts for textiles and
garments gained 1.43 percent to 669 million US dollars; those of
medicines and health products were up by 10.02 percent to 99
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Minerals and metals export orders dipped 12.54 percent to 232
million US dollars. Those of cereals and edible oils and native
produce stood at 351 million US dollars, down 11.15 percent.
