<HEADLINE> Foreign Tourism Agencies Keen on China's Travel Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Increasing foreign tourism
agencies and airlines are eyeing the great potential of China's
travel market, as many better-to-do Chinese people now prefer to
spend their holidays aboard.
</P>
<P>
In April Malaysia Airlines and Ansett Australia opened offices
in Shanghai as part of their business expansion in China. The two
airlines have begun twice-weekly direct services between Kuala
Lumpur and Shanghai, and between Sydney and Shanghai, today's
China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
During the New Year's Day and Spring Festival holidays this
year, all tickets for tour groups heading for Malaysia, Thailand,
Singapore, Hong Kong and Macao were sold out, said an official
with China International Travel Service (CITS).
</P>
<P>
With travel booming to Southeast Asia, Chinese people began
to select long-distance and exotic countries as their destination.
</P>
<P>
About 54,000 Chinese visited Australia in 1996, a 26.7 percent
increase from the previous year, according to an Australia Tourist
Commission (ATC) official.
</P>
<P>
ATC is planning to open office in China this year as part of
its effort to meet the demand of the growing number of Asian
travellers to Australia. The number of visitors from Asia to
Australia is expected to double by the year 2001 to reach 2.4
million.
</P>
<P>
As many as 600,000 Chinese are estimated to visit Australia
annually by the year 2001, becoming one of major source markets
for tourism trade in Australia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
