<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica has Healthy Coffee Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican coffee growers are
expected to export 550,000 to 600,000 sacks of coffee over the
five months ending before September, the Coffee Institute (ICAFE)
said today.
</P>
<P>
About 60,000 sacks are expected to be shipped to Japan, it said.
</P>
<P>
Coffee growers in Costa Rica have benefited recently by price
increases in coffee beans. But the ICAFE warned that they should
be prudent in view of price fluctuations on the international
market.
</P>
<P>
Coffee prices have been rising after several years of
depression, and following the decision of producing countries to
create an association and to withhold 20 percent of its coffee
beans from world markets.
</P>
<P>
The price for a sack of coffee, which weigbhs 60 kilograms, has
reached slightly more than 214 U.S. dollars on the international
market.
</P>
<P>
The average price of Costa Rican coffee this year was 133
U.S. dollars a sack, compared with 114 dollars for the previous
harvest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
