<HEADLINE> Austria to Send Troops to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Austrian government decided
today to send troops to join the multinational protection force in
Albania, a Government news release said.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian Council of Ministers agreed to send 115 troops on
Thursday to be part of the Italian-led multinational protection
force.
</P>
<P>
The decision was to go to the National Council (lower house of
the parliament) this evening for approval.
</P>
<P>
Albania was plunged into chaos in early March after the
collapse of dozens of pyramid savings schemes, which left
thousands of Albanians penniless.
</P>
<P>
Protests turned violent after armed rebels looted army depots
and took over several towns in the south.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian government had to call for international aid and
military intervention to help restore order in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian government said the decision to send troops was
made in line with the United Nations Security Council Resolution
1101 adopted on March 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the three-month mission, the Austrian soldiers will be
responsible for the security of the headquarters of the protection
force and other international organizations in Tirana. The main
task of the multinational force is to help implement emergency
relief operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
