<HEADLINE> Japan Thanks Peru for Hostage Rescue Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto today expressed his gratitude to Peruvian President
Alberto Fujimori for rescuing all of the hostages besieged in the
Japanese ambassador's residence in Lima.
</P>
<P>
"I express my gratitude from my heart to President Fujimori and
the Peruvian government, which conducted the triumphant rescue
operations," Hashimoto told an early morning conference.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said that all of the Japanese captives, 12
businessmen and 12 diplomats, were released safely.
</P>
<P>
However, the Japanese prime minister regretted that he was not
informed of the rescue operation beforehand.
</P>
<P>
Japan will send Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda to Lima later
today, Hashimoto said.
</P>
<P>
A special Peruvian command squad stormed the Japanese
ambassador's residence in Lima Tuesday afternoon, rescuing all of
the 72 hostages.
</P>
<P>
The heavily armed Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement rebels
assaulted the residence on December 17 last year during a cocktail
party marking the Japanese emperor's birthday and took almost 500
hostages. They quickly released most of them, but had held 72 male
hostages to press their demand for the freedom of their jailed
comrades. 
</P>
