<HEADLINE> SDB To Provide Funds for Major Railway Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The State Development Bank (SDB)
plans to inject 1.41 billion US dollars this year to bolster
China's key railway construction projects, today's "China Daily"
reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper uses the bank sources as saying
that in the first quarter of this year, about 265 million US
dollars went to the railway projects. So far, the bank has loaned
3.95 billion US dollars to 49 railway projects, accounting for 12
percent of the bank's total loans.
</P>
<P>
SDB, a policy bank set up in 1994, is designed to support the
construction of State infrastructural facilities. It financed some
large projects as Beijing-Kowloon, Baoji-Zhongwei, Nanning-Kunming
and Houma-Yueshan railways. It adopted 13-14-year loans for the
large and medium railway projects instead of the eight-year loans
issued by other domestic banks.
</P>
<P>
SDB also established special loans for railway electrification,
and about 132 million US dollars went into the sector in 1996. It
granted loans totalling 325 million US dollars to support regional
railroad construction.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials said during 1996-2000 period, railway
construction will continue to be a priority for SDB. The bank
plans to raise its ratio of loans for railway construction along
with the power, oil and national gas and petrochemical industries
to about 50 percent from the present 47 percent, the paper
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
