<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebels: New Clashes Won't Derail Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The third round of preliminary
talks between the Philippine government and the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) will be held today as scheduled despite
renewed clashes between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Ghazali Gaafar, who is in charge of the MILF's political
affairs, said their technical committee on cessation of
hostilities was ready to discuss with its government counterparts
the forging of an expanded ceasefire, local press reported.
</P>
<P>
Both sides earlier agreed to a ceasefire in Central Mindanao,
known as the Buldon ceasefire after having a number of clashes
earlier this year. An expanded truce would include all other areas
where the MILF operated.
</P>
<P>
According to Gaafar, the coming peace talks were very crucial
since it will also discuss the future timetable for the MILF to
enter formal peace talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the military clashed in a number of places last
week. At least two soldiers and 25 rebels were killed in the
incidents. The two sides blamed each other for first provoking the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
Gaafar has called on the Interim Ceasefire Monitoring
Committee, an independent third-party formed to oversee the Buldon
truce, to start monitoring truce violations in Buldon in
Maguindanao province, where thousands of soldiers and MILF
fighters are facing a standoff.
</P>
<P>
MILF is a splinter group of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front which signed a peace agreement with the
government last year. With 12,000 fighters, the MILF is now the
biggest rebel group in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
