<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Labor Lead Shrinks to Five Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Britain's general election was
thrown wide open as opposition Labor Party's huge lead over the
ruling Conservatives in most opinion polls reduced dramatically to
just five points from 14 last week.
</P>
<P>
According to an opinon poll released in Wednesday's "the
Guardian" newspaper, Labor was now on 42 percentage point, down
three points from last week, while the Conservatives was at 37
percent with a rise of six points, and the third largest party
Liberal Democrats at 14 percent, down five points.
</P>
<P>
The ICM/Guardian poll, which was conducted on Sunday and
Monday, is the first poll giving the party a single-figure lead
since November 1993, and its fall to 43 percent is Labor Party's
worst rating under Tony Blair's leadership since July 1994.
</P>
<P>
ICM's poll confirms a Conservative comeback since Prime
Minister John Major was forced by internal pressure to confront
the EU question head-on at his press conference a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The poll shows that the Conservatives get more support than
Labor on Europe. Asked which party they think will best represent
Britain's interest in EU, 36 percent chose the Conservatives with
Labor 28. The ruling party has also moved ahead of Labor on best
policies for dealing with the economy, a traditionally accurate
signpost to the public's voting intention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
