<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil is going to accept credit cards from
Argentina, announced Andres Espinosa, president of Visa credit
cards in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The executive pointed out that the measure will bolster the
integration between the countries of the Southern Common Market
(Mercosur, its acronym in Spanish). Argentine as well as
international credit cards will be accepted in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The president of Visa in Brazil said that this measure will
enable Argentine tourists to have, as of today, a new option to
make purchases in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- During the first 2 months of this year Costa Rican
exports of fresh fish amounted to 16.08 million U.S. dollars, an
increase of 497.8 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Of tha total, overseas sales rose to 11.77 million dollars in
January and to 4.31 million dollars in February.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica has an abundance of water resources. In 1996, its
exports of fish climbed to 113.7 million dollars, 3 percent of the
total amount of the country's foreign sales.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay reported a trade deficit of 119.7
million dollars this January which was on top of the 25 million
dollars reported at the end of 1996, said the central bank.
</P>
<P>
During the month analyzed, its exports reached 181.5 million
dollars and its imports 301.2 million dollars with increases of
6.7 and 26.8 percent respectively over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Central American, Mexican and Dominican Republic
Agriculture Ministers declared a state of emergency for the region
last week to facilitate measures against the "deadly yellowing
disease" a plague which destroys coconut trees and which has been
detected in Honduras and Belize.
</P>
<P>
The ministers who gathered Thursday and Friday in San Pedro
Sula in northern Honduras attend an inauguration on the Caribbean
island of Roatan, of a reforestation project of 4,800 coconut
tress resistent to this plague.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombian petroleum exports will exceed
620,000 barrels per day in 1998, said Ecopetrol, Colombia's
state-owned oil company.
</P>
<P>
Of that volume, 350,000 barrels will correspond to Ecopetro
and the remainder to companies associated with that state-owned
company. (to be continued)


nnnn
</P>
