<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four-Month Hostage Crisis Ends in Lima </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian armed forces stormed
Japanese Ambassador Morihisa Aoki's residence in Lima this
afternoon, ending a four-month-long hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
Sound of gunfire and explosions were heard at 15:20 hours and
smoke could be seen inside the residence of Japanese Ambassador
Morihisa Aoki.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said that the assault had freed all 72
hostages, with Supreme Court Judge Carlos Giusti killed.
</P>
<P>
But Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori said all the hostages
were safe, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The assault killed all of the roughly 15 Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary (MRTA) guerrillas, who stormed the ambassador's
residence during a cocktail party on December 17 and held more
than 500 guests hostage, police said.
</P>
<P>
The guerrillas freed most of the hostages later but held 72 men
as bargaining chips to press their demand for the release of over
400 jailed comrades. No one was injured or killed until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Less than an hour after the assault, which also freed the
brother of the president, Fujimori entered the compound, wearing a
bulletproof vest.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori, waving a Peruvian flag from a bus that took the
former hostages to a hospital for checkup, said all the 72
hostages were freed alive.
</P>
<P>
"We've received 72 friends alive and well," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
