<HEADLINE> Youngest Table Tennis Player Here for Experience </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 23 (Xinhua) -- English table tennis
player Katy Parker, at the age of 12 years and 144 days, will
become the youngest English athlete to play in a world
championships on May Day.
</P>
<P>
Parker, daughter of Jill Hammersley, the former European
champion, will partner Michael Chan, 13, in the mixed doubles at
the 44th World Table Tennis Championships, which begin with the
team event in Mnchester on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
She began playing table tennis at the age of six, standing on a
box to see above the table, and won national championships at
under-10, under-11 and under-12.
</P>
<P>
"She's level headed and a clever player," said Carole Moore,
chairman of the junior selection committee of the English Table
Tennis Association. "I'm sure she will give a good amount of
herself."
</P>
<P>
Parker's parents support her selection for the championships.
Both are aware of the dangers of burn-out, which prompted the
tennis prodigy, Jennifer Capriati, at 14 years and 90 days the
youngest competitor in the modern era at Wimbledon, to drop out of
the game temporarily.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of kids who are pushed into playing give up," Parker's
mother said. "It's up to her how much she plays. I'm not worried
that she will be frightened by the occasion. We've said to
her: 'You're here for experience."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
