<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OHR Says Sharing Concerns Over Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Office of High
Representative (OHR) said on Tuesday that it shares the concerns
expressed by Alija Izetbegovic, chairman of the Bosnian
presidency, over the slow implementation of the Dayton peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, we fully share president Izetbegovic's concerns about
the status of implementation," said Simon Haselock, spokesman for
OHR, the organization in charge of the peace accords
implementation.
</P>
<P>
Izetbegovic expressed his concerns in an assessment on the
implementation process which he presented on Monday to the
representatives from the 5-nation contact group and Islamic
nations as well as High Representative Carl Bildt.
</P>
<P>
The assessment listed nine areas in which provisions of the
Dayton accords have either been violated or implemented slowly,
such as the institutions, return of refugees and continued
inter-entity border disputes.
</P>
<P>
Haselock said that the OHR has also underlined the importance
of common institutions to the peace process, and appealed again to
all the Bosnian parties involved to make sure they make these
common institutions such as the national parliament and central
bank effective. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Optimistic on Chemical Weapons Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today said he was optimistic that the Senate will ratify the
Chemical Weapons Convention before it takes effect on April 29.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for a trip to flood-ravaged North Dakota,
Clinton told reporters that Vice President Al Gore and others in
the administration had been working to win the Senate approval of
the treaty.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that the administration has agreed with treaty
opponents on the 28 "clarifying" amendments shows "the good faith
in which we have proceeded."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "We have worked very hard on this, and I'm
actually quite optimistic."
</P>
<P>
The treaty, which bans the development, production,
stockpiling, transferring and use of chemical weapons, has been
ratified by 74 countries.
</P>
<P>
Opponents of the treaty in the U.S. Senate argued that the
treaty is "unenforceable" and "not global", demanding the U.S.
join it after Iran, Libya and Russia agree to participate the
convention.
</P>
<P>
A full Senate vote is scheduled on Thursday after debate on
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
