<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Imposes New Sanctions on Burma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Tuesday announced to ban new investment in Burma as fresh measures
to force the Burmese government to act in an accordance with U.S.
dictations.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released on Tuesday, Clinton said: "I have taken
this step in response to a continuing pattern of repression by the
State Law and Order Restoration Council in Burma."
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said the move did not affect existing
investments there.
</P>
<P>
At the State Department, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
told reporters that Clinton made the decision because "the
repression by the Military authorities of the democratic
opposition in Burma has deepened," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
Details of the provisions, including the effect on
foreign-based subsidiaries of U.S. companies, were being worked
out, State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said.
</P>
<P>
Washington would try to persuade other countries to join it in
isolating Burma, Burns said at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
"We will be very aggressive, obviously, in talking to our Asian
and European allies and partners about this issue and hope that
they may follow suit," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has halted direct financial assistance and
blocked much international aid since the State Law and Order
Restoration Council took power in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
