<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Jump Higher on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial average
jumped to its second biggest-point gain ever today, rising to its
highest level in nearly a month, as long-term interest rates fell
back toward 7 percent in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow gained 173.38 points, or 2.6 percent, to 6,833.59. The
blue-chip barometer recouped 442 points so far this month.
</P>
<P>
Today's gain put the Dow above 6,800 for the first time since
late March and beat last Tuesday's 135-point rally, which had been
the biggest point gain since a 186.84-point jump two days after
the Black Monday crash of 1987.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by more than a 3-to-2
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 501.98
million shares, up sharply from Monday's 393.65 million.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 14.27 to 774.64, and
the NYSE composite index rose 6.44 to 405.84.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 8.79 to 1,212.74, but the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 6.51 to 544.96.
</P>
<P>
The Dow still stands about 250 points shy of its all-time best
close at 7,085.16, set March 11.
</P>
<P>
Most broad measures also surged this afternoon as bonds rallied
after an encouraging auction of new Treasury securities.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices rose, the benchmark yield on the 30-year
Treasury bond fell to 7.04 percent. A week ago, the long-bond
yield rose to a nine-month high of 7.17 percent amid mounting
inflation jitters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
