<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Issues Report Linking Environment with Diplomacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
today issued its first annual report on the environment, saying it
will place a priority on environmental issues in the country's
foreign relations.
</P>
<P>
The report, which was piled up on a decision by former State
Secretary Warren Christopher to integrate the environment into
American foreign policy, said the U.S. will focus on climate
change, toxic chemicals, species extinction, deforestation and
marine degradation.
</P>
<P>
It said that regional hubs to promote environmental policies
would be opened this year in U.S. embassies in Costa Rica,
Uzbekistan, Ethiopia, Nepal, Jordan and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Issuing the 32-page report, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said that the U.S. seeks "an outcome in which the
industrialized nations who emit the largest amount of greenhouse
gases today will accept legally binding targets, and in which
developing nations...acknowledge their obligations for the
future."
</P>
<P>
"We will be placing a steadily increased priority on
environmental and related global issues in many of our key
bilateral relationships," she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the link between the environment and foreign
policy will enable the U.S. to have another tool like human rights
to play power politics and hegemony in the world.
</P>
<P>
The State Department issued annual report on human rights
blaming other countries except the U.S. itself on human rights
situation. The measure is widely regarded as a violation of
international norms since it interferes other countries' internal
affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970423.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Accuses Iraq of Flying Pilgrims Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States attacked
Iraq on Tuesday for its sending helicopters to pick up Muslim
pilgrims from Saudi Arabia, saying the move was "trying to pick a
fight" with the only superpower in the world.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Iraq flew several helicopters on Monday and
Tuesday over U.S.-enforced no-fly zone in southern Iraq to the
Iraq-Saudi border in an effort to ferry Iraqi citizens back from
last week's pilgrimage to the Muslim holy cities of Mecca dn
Medina in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The United States, irritated by Iraq's move in defiance of its
earlier warning not to do anything provocative, said it would not
tolerate any "violation" by Iraqi President Saddam Hussein of U.N.
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"What Iraq seems to be doing is engaging in a high-wire act of
political provocation. They're trying to pick a fight," State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said at a regular news
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"He (Saddam) shouldn't test the resolve of the United States,"
Burns said. "Any type of military provocation, of course, will not
succeed because the United States and our allies will continue to
enforce the no-fly, no-drive zones."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Bill Clinton told reporters at the White
House before leaving for the Midwest that the United States would
"continue to observe the no-fly zone and continue to support the
embargo until he (Saddam) lives up to the conditions of the United
Nations resolutions."
</P>
<P>
"We support people in exercising their religious liberties and
in living out their religious convictions everywhere in the
world.... But we don't want to see religion, in effect, used and
distorted in a way to try to avoid the international obligations
that are imposed," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the Pentagon, spokesman Kenneth Bacon told reporters there
had been no change in U.S. policy regarding the no-fly zone, but
he admitted Iraq was not mobilizing its forces to confront the
United States and its allies.
</P>
<P>
"We can discriminate between relatively small-scale
humanitarian operations and large-scale military movements," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Nizar Hamdoun, Iraq's ambassador to the United Nations, said in
an interview with the British Broadcasting Corp. that his country
was not seeking a confrontation with Washington. He, however,
stressed that his country does not recognize the no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
"It is illegal. It has nothing to do with any Security Council
resolution," he said.
</P>
<P>
On April 9, Iraq flew 104 pilgrims to Saudi Arabia for the
pilgrimage to Mecca and Medina, and the United States wanted the
U.N. Security Councils to condemn the flight as a violation of the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council issued a statement calling on Iraq
not to fly more planes without its consent, but stopped short of
terming the flight a breach of the embargo as the United States
had wished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
